-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Lucy Doolan]] \n| 10 || 4 || 23 || 3 || 2.30\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sarah Tsukigawa]] \n| 4 || 1 || 23 || 0 || 5.75\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Aimee Watkins|Aimee Mason]] \n| 9 || 0 || 28 || 2 || 3.11\n|}\n\n'''Match officials'''\n* On-field [[umpire (cricket)|umpires]]: [[Steve Davis (umpire)|Steve Davis]] and [[Brian Jerling]]\n* [[Third umpire]]: [[Tyron Wijewardene]]\n* [[Match referee]]: [[Brian Aldridge (cricketer)|Brian Aldridge]]\n* [[Fourth umpire|Reserve umpire]]: [[Jeff Brookes]]\n\n'''Key'''\n* {{asterisk}} \u2013 [[Captain (cricket)|Captain]]\n* {{dagger}} \u2013 [[Wicket-keeper]]\n* c ''Fielder'' \u2013 Indicates that the batter was dismissed by a catch by the named [[Fielding (cricket)|fielder]]\n* b ''Bowler'' \u2013 Indicates which [[Bowling (cricket)|bowler]] gains credit for the dismissal\n* lbw \u2013 Indicates the batter was dismissed [[leg before wicket]]\n* st \u2013 Indicates the batter was [[stumped]]\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe ICC awarded England US$45,000 for their cup win, while New Zealand received $25,000.<ref name=\"tears\"/> Shaw, who had not expected to play, said after the match; \"I started the day crying, I finished it crying, but we won a World Cup in between\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/23/women-england-cricket-world-cup |title=England win the World Cup |last=Booth |first=Lawrence |author-link=Lawrence Booth (cricket writer) |work=The Guardian |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> New Zealand's captain, Tiffen, reflected after the match, \"Maybe there were some nerves in amongst the camp. We didn't hype it up to be anything more than another day at the office, unfortunately it was a bad day at the office.\"<ref name=\"tears\"/> The team of the tournament included seven finalists: England's Edwards was selected as captain, and was joined by teammates Brunt, Marsh, Claire Taylor and Sarah Taylor. Bates and Pulford represented New Zealand in the team, while Devine was named as the team's twelfth woman. Claire Taylor, who finished the tournament as the leading run-scorer, was named as the player of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/396488.html |title=Five England players in World Cup XI |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> The month after the final, Taylor became the first woman to be selected as one of [[Wisden Cricketers of the Year|''Wisden's'' Cricketers of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/5096209/Claire-Taylor-the-first-woman-to-be-named-among-the-Wisden-Cricketers-of-the-Year.html |title=Claire Taylor the first woman to be named among the Wisden Cricketers of the Year |last=Berry |first=Scyld |authorlink=Scyld Berry |work=The Daily Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |location=London |date=3 April 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Both Taylor and Edwards were awarded [[Order of the British Empire|MBEs]] for their services to cricket; Edwards received hers in the [[2009 Birthday Honours]], while Taylor's came in the [[2010 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Skirting the Boundary: A History of Women's Cricket |last=Duncan |first=Isabelle |year=2013 |publisher=[[The Robson Press]] |location=London |isbn=978-1-84954-546-4 |pages=151\u2013153}}</ref>\n\nThe England team flew back to the United Kingdom in [[economy class]]; Mitchell highlighted the contrast with the [[England cricket team|England men's team]], who \"fly business as standard\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2009/03/world_champions.shtml |title=World champions return home |last=Mitchell |first=Alison |author-link=Alison Mitchell |work=BBC Sport |date=24 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> They held a reception at Lord's in London upon their return, but the former [[Minister for Sport and Civil Society|sports minister]], [[Richard Caborn]], lamented the low-key celebrations, saying that \"I would have a Number 10 reception, a reception at the House of Commons, and, at the appropriate time, in the Lords.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/25/england-womens-world-cup-winners |title=England women's cricket team bring back the cup \u2013 and the pride |last=Gibson |first=Owen |work=The Guardian |date=25 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> In her history of women's cricket, Rafaelle Nicholson was critical of some of the reporting on the final, saying that \"coverage increasingly appears to compare women's cricket with the men's game, and to treat the male version as 'real cricket'\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MkXOxAEACAAJ |title=Ladies and Lords: A History of Women's Cricket in Britain |last=Nicholson |first=Rafaelle |year=2019 |publisher=[[Peter Lang (publisher)|Peter Lang]] |isbn=978-1-78874-294-8 |page=loc. 7916 |nopp=true}}</ref> The English journalists Simon Wilde and [[Lawrence Booth (cricket writer)|Lawrence Booth]] credited the contracts introduced in 2008 as being critical to England's success.<ref name=\"wilde\"/><ref name=\"feet\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/englands-women-have-the-world-at-their-feet-kwsx05xkrkc |title=England\u2019s women have the world at their feet: Team can complete a historic treble by winning the World Twenty20 final against New Zealand at Lord\u2019s today |last=Booth |first=Lawrence |authorlink=Lawrence Booth (cricket writer) |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=21 June 2009 |accessdate=21 April 2020 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Booth highlighted the contrast with New Zealand's captain, Tiffin, who had retired after the World Cup, claiming: \"If I was paid properly, I'd still be playing.\"<ref name=\"feet\"/>\n\nThe two sides met again three months later to contest the final of the [[2009 ICC Women's World Twenty20|2009 Women's World Twenty20]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwt202009/engine/match/355990.html |title=Final: England Women v New Zealand Women at Lord's, Jun 21, 2009 |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 April 2012}}</ref> England once again won the contest, and in doing so became the first team of either gender to be champions in all three cricketing formats: [[Women's Test cricket|Test]], [[Women's One Day International|One Day International]] and [[Women's Twenty20 International|Twenty20]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwt202009/content/story/409994.html |title=All-conquering England take title |last=Narayanan |first=Nishi |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 June 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> Each of the top four in the 2009 tournament automatically qualified for the [[2013 Women's Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/cricket/report/kiwi-bates-does-a-sehwag-world-cup/20090319.htm |title=Kiwi Bates does a Sehwag in World Cup |work=[[Rediff.com]] |date=19 March 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Neither England nor New Zealand reached the final of that tournament, but instead met in the third-place playoff, which England won by four wickets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.ndtv.com/icc-womens-world-cup/news/203626-charlotte-edwards-guides-england-to-third-spot-in-womens-world-cup |title=Charlotte Edwards guides England to third spot in Women's World Cup |agency=Press Trust of India |publisher=[[NDTV]] |date=15 February 2013 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{2009 Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England women's cricket team}}\n{{New Zealand women's national cricket team}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:2008\u201309 Australian women's cricket season|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in English women's cricket|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in New Zealand cricket|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in New Zealand women's sport|cricket]]\n[[Category:2009 Women's Cricket World Cup|!]]\n[[Category:England women's national cricket team matches|World Cup 2009]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women's national cricket team matches|World Cup 2009]]\n[[Category:Women's Cricket World Cup finals]]\n", "name_user": "Harrias", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAftermath:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2009_Women%27s_Cricket_World_Cup_Final"}
{"title_page": "Richard Cohen (fencer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| image          =\n| name           = Richard Cohen\n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = British\n| residence      = New York City\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1947|5|9|df=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[Birmingham]], England\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| website        = richardcohenauthor.com\n| country        = England (1970-1986); Northern Ireland (1986-present)\n| sport          = [[Fencing]] (sabre)\n| collegeteam    = \n| club           = \n| team           = \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          = \n| retired        = \n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    =\n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport | Fencing}}\t\n{{MedalCountry | {{ENG}} }}\t\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games|British Commonwealth Games]]}}\t\n{{MedalGold| [[1970 British Commonwealth Games|1970 Edinburgh]] | [[Fencing at the 1970 British Commonwealth Games|sabre team]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[1970 British Commonwealth Games|1970 Edinburgh]] | [[Fencing at the 1970 British Commonwealth Games|sabre individual]]}}\n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''Richard A Cohen''' (born 9 May 1947) is a retired British [[Fencing|fencer]] who competed at three [[Olympic Games]]<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/co/richard-cohen-1.html |title=Richard Cohen Olympic Results |accessdate=13 February 2011 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref> and the author of ''Chasing the Sun'', the story of man's relationship to that star, and ''By the Sword'', a history of sword fighting. He is the founder of the book publisher Richard Cohen Books.\n\n==Fencing Career==\nCohen was born in [[Birmingham]], England, to a Jewish father and an Irish Catholic mother.  He learned to fence while  at [[Downside School]], near Bath.<ref>[http://www.veterans-fencing.co.uk/wc2006/eng/support.shtml World Veterans Fencing Championship]</ref> He was British [[Sabre (fencing)|Sabre]] Champion five times and was selected for the British team in four Olympics from 1972 to 1984, although he did not compete at the Moscow Olympics because of a sporting [[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|boycott]].<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/by-the-sword-gladiators-musketeers-samurai-warriors-swashbucklers-and-olympians-by-richard-cohen-610607.html Book review, The Independent, 11 December 2002.] He was Commonwealth sabre champion in 1982 and won the prestigious Paris Open in 1981. Retrieved 26 March 2009.</ref>\n\nHe represented [[England at the 1970 British Commonwealth Games|England]] and won a [[gold medal]] in the team sabre and a [[bronze medal]] in the individual sabre, at the [[1970 British Commonwealth Games]] in [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://teamengland.org/commonwealth-games-history/edinburgh-1970/athletes|title=1970 Athletes|publisher=Team England}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://teamengland.org/commonwealth-games-history/edinburgh-1970|title=Edinburgh, 1970 Team|publisher=Team England}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecgf.com/results/athletes/46554|title=Athletes and results|publisher=Commonwealth Games Federation}}</ref> and won the individual saber gold medal at the fencing Commonwealth championships in 1982, held in Bridport, England. \n\nCohen was World Veterans\u2019 Sabre Champion in 2004, 2005, 2008 and 2009 and has been European sabre champion nine times, making him the most successful single-weapon fencer of veteran fencing.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} He won the national veteran saber championships a record fourteen times.\n\n==Publishing career==\nWhile competing as a fencer, he worked for book publishers, editing much of the early work of [[Jeffrey Archer]], as well as John le Carre, Anthony Burgess, Kingsley Amis, Sebastian Faulks and Fay Weldon. In 1985 he became publishing director of [[Hutchinson (publisher)|Hutchinson]] and in 1992 of [[Hodder & Stoughton]]. In 1995 he founded his own publishers, Richard Cohen Books, which won the ''Sunday Times'' Small publisher of the Year award in 1998.<ref>[http://www.kingston.ac.uk/postgraduate-course/publishing-ma/who-teaches-this-course.html Publishing MA: Who teaches this course, Kingston University.] Retrieved on 25 November 2010.</ref> In 1991 and 1992 he was program director of the Cheltenham Festival of Literature, recording world record audiences of over 30,000 both years. Since moving to America in 1999, he has edited the No. 1 bestseller Leadership by [[Rudy Giuliani]], all seven books by [[Madeleine Albright]], [[David Boies' Courting Justice]], and the Pulitzer Prizewinning biography of Malcolm X by [[Manning Marable]]. Cohen wrote a history of fencing, ''By the Sword'' (2002), with the subtitle ''A History of Gladiators, Musketeers, Samurai, Swashbucklers, and Olympic Champions''.;<ref>Richard Cohen, ''By the Sword'', 2002, Random House </ref> a large-scale history of the Sun, ''Chasing the Sun, The Epic Story of the Star that Gives Us Life'', 2010, a BBC Book of the Week, Random House, a book about literature and how to write, ''How To Write Like Tolstoy'', May 2016, Random House, and The History Makers, 2020 Random House, a history of historians from Herodotus to the present day. He appeared in the James Bond film, ''[[Die Another Day]]'' (2002).\n\n==Personal life==\nHe has two sons and a daughter and lives in [[New York City]] with his wife Kathy Robbins, a literary agent. His son Guy Cohen won a bronze medal for Great Britain at the [[2013 Maccabiah Games]] in men\u2019s \u00e9p\u00e9e, and his daughter Mary fenced in \u00e9p\u00e9e, Richard Cohen in both foil and saber.<ref>https://www.thejc.com/sport/sport-news/fencer-cohen-wins-gb-s-first-maccabiah-medal-1.47378</ref> His daughter, Mary (born 1986), was British \u00e9p\u00e9e champion in 2006, 2011 and 2018, and was a member of the British team at World and European championships from 2002 till 2019. In 2010 father (for Northern Ireland) and daughter (for England) competed in the same Commonwealth championships, the first father and daughter to do so, Cohen at age 63 coming 12th in the saber and winning the veterans saber (over 40), a first gold medal for Northern Ireland in Commonwealth fencing. In June 2017 he was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society of Literature.<ref>[http://www.randomhouse.com/author/results.pperl?authorid=5297 Richard Cohen, Random House authors]. Retrieved 26 March 2009.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://richardcohenauthor.com// Official website]\n*[http://www.olympics.org.uk/athleterecord.aspx?at=854 British Olympic Association]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cohen, Richard}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:People educated at Downside School]]\n[[Category:English writers]]\n[[Category:British male fencers]]\n[[Category:Olympic fencers of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Fencers at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Fencers at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Fencers at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in fencing]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games gold medallists for England]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games bronze medallists for England]]\n[[Category:English people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2013 Maccabiah Games]]\n[[Category:Maccabiah Games fencers]]\n[[Category:Maccabiah Games competitors for Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Fencers at the 1970 British Commonwealth Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| image          =\n| name           = Richard Cohen\n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = British\n| residence      = New York City\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1947|5|9|df=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[Birmingham]], England\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| website        = richardcohenauthor.com\n| country        = England (1970-1986); Northern Ireland (1986-present)\n| sport          = [[Fencing]] (sabre)\n| collegeteam    = \n| club           = \n| team           = \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          = \n| retired        = \n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    =\n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport | Fencing}}\t\n{{MedalCountry | {{ENG}} }}\t\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games|British Commonwealth Games]]}}\t\n{{MedalGold| [[1970 British Commonwealth Games|1970 Edinburgh]] | [[Fencing at the 1970 British Commonwealth Games|sabre team]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[1970 British Commonwealth Games|1970 Edinburgh]] | [[Fencing at the 1970 British Commonwealth Games|sabre individual]]}}\n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''Richard A Cohen''' (born 9 May 1947) is a retired British [[Fencing|fencer]] who competed at three [[Olympic Games]]<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/co/richard-cohen-1.html |title=Richard Cohen Olympic Results |accessdate=13 February 2011 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref> and the author of ''Chasing the Sun'', the story of man's relationship to that star, and ''By the Sword'', a history of sword fighting. He is the founder of the book publisher Richard Cohen Books.\n\n==Fencing Career==\nCohen was born in [[Birmingham]], England, to a Jewish father and an Irish Catholic mother.  He learned to fence while  at [[Downside School]], near Bath.<ref>[http://www.veterans-fencing.co.uk/wc2006/eng/support.shtml World Veterans Fencing Championship]</ref> He was British [[Sabre (fencing)|Sabre]] Champion five times and was selected for the British team in four Olympics from 1972 to 1984, although he did not compete at the Moscow Olympics because of a sporting [[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|boycott]].<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/by-the-sword-gladiators-musketeers-samurai-warriors-swashbucklers-and-olympians-by-richard-cohen-610607.html Book review, The Independent, 11 December 2002.] He was Commonwealth sabre champion in 1982 and won the prestigious Paris Open in 1981. Retrieved 26 March 2009.</ref>\n\nHe represented [[England at the 1970 British Commonwealth Games|England]] and won a [[gold medal]] in the team sabre and a [[bronze medal]] in the individual sabre, at the [[1970 British Commonwealth Games]] in [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://teamengland.org/commonwealth-games-history/edinburgh-1970/athletes|title=1970 Athletes|publisher=Team England}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://teamengland.org/commonwealth-games-history/edinburgh-1970|title=Edinburgh, 1970 Team|publisher=Team England}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecgf.com/results/athletes/46554|title=Athletes and results|publisher=Commonwealth Games Federation}}</ref> and the individial saber gold medal at the fencing Commonwealth championships in 1982, held in Bridport, England. \n\nCohen was World Veterans\u2019 Sabre Champion in 2004, 2005, 2008 and 2009 and has been European sabre champion nine times, making him the most successful single-weapon fencer of veteran fencing.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} He won the national veteran saber championships a record fourteen times.\n\n==Publishing career==\nWhile competing as a fencer, he worked for book publishers, editing much of the early work of [[Jeffrey Archer]], as well as John le Carre, Anthony Burgess, Kingsley Amis, Sebastian Faulks and Fay Weldon. In 1985 he became publishing director of [[Hutchinson (publisher)|Hutchinson]] and in 1992 of [[Hodder & Stoughton]]. In 1995 he founded his own publishers, Richard Cohen Books, which won the ''Sunday Times'' Small publisher of the Year award in 1998.<ref>[http://www.kingston.ac.uk/postgraduate-course/publishing-ma/who-teaches-this-course.html Publishing MA: Who teaches this course, Kingston University.] Retrieved on 25 November 2010.</ref> In 1991 and 1992 he was program director of the Cheltenham Festival of Literature, recording world record audiences of over 30,000 both years. Since moving to America in 1999, he has edited the No. 1 bestseller Leadership by [[Rudy Giuliani]], all seven books by [[Madeleine Albright]], [[David Boies' Courting Justice]], and the Pulitzer Prizewinning biography of Malcolm X by [[Manning Marable]]. Cohen wrote a history of fencing, ''By the Sword'' (2002), with the subtitle ''A History of Gladiators, Musketeers, Samurai, Swashbucklers, and Olympic Champions''.;<ref>Richard Cohen, ''By the Sword'', 2002, Random House </ref> a large-scale history of the Sun, ''Chasing the Sun, The Epic Story of the Star that Gives Us Life'', 2010, a BBC Book of the Week, Random House, a book about literature and how to write, ''How To Write Like Tolstoy'', May 2016, Random House, and The History Makers, 2020 Random House, a history of historians from Herodotus to the present day. He appeared in the James Bond film, ''[[Die Another Day]]'' (2002).\n\n==Personal life==\nHe has two sons and a daughter and lives in [[New York City]] with his wife Kathy Robbins, a literary agent. His son Guy Cohen won a bronze medal for Great Britain at the [[2013 Maccabiah Games]] in men\u2019s \u00e9p\u00e9e, and his daughter Mary fenced in \u00e9p\u00e9e, Richard Cohen in both foil and saber.<ref>https://www.thejc.com/sport/sport-news/fencer-cohen-wins-gb-s-first-maccabiah-medal-1.47378</ref> His daughter, Mary (born 1986), was British \u00e9p\u00e9e champion in 2006, 2011 and 2018, and was a member of the British team at World and European championships from 2002 till 2019. In 2010 father (for Northern Ireland) and daughter (for England) competed in the same Commonwealth championships, the first father and daughter to do so, Cohen at age 63 coming 12th in the saber and winning the veterans saber (over 40), a first gold medal for Northern Ireland in Commonwealth fencing. In June 2017 he was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society of Literature.<ref>[http://www.randomhouse.com/author/results.pperl?authorid=5297 Richard Cohen, Random House authors]. Retrieved 26 March 2009.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://richardcohenauthor.com// Official website]\n*[http://www.olympics.org.uk/athleterecord.aspx?at=854 British Olympic Association]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cohen, Richard}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:People educated at Downside School]]\n[[Category:English writers]]\n[[Category:British male fencers]]\n[[Category:Olympic fencers of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Fencers at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Fencers at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Fencers at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in fencing]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games gold medallists for England]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games bronze medallists for England]]\n[[Category:English people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2013 Maccabiah Games]]\n[[Category:Maccabiah Games fencers]]\n[[Category:Maccabiah Games competitors for Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Fencers at the 1970 British Commonwealth Games]]\n", "name_user": "Richard cohen author", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFencing Career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Cohen_(fencer)"}
{"title_page": "List of United States presidential assassination attempts and plots", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\nAssassination attempts and plots on the [[president of the United States]] have been numerous, ranging from the early 19th century to the 2010s. More than 30 attempts to kill an [[incumbent]] or former president, or a [[President-elect of the United States|president-elect]] have been made since the early 19th century. Four sitting presidents have been killed: [[Abraham Lincoln]] (1865), [[James A. Garfield]] (1881), [[William McKinley]] (1901), and [[John F. Kennedy]] (1963). Additionally, two presidents have been injured in attempted assassinations: [[Theodore Roosevelt]] (1912; former president at the time) and [[Ronald Reagan]] (1981). In all of these cases, the attack weapon used was a firearm.\n\nAlthough historian James W. Clarke has suggested that most American assassinations were politically motivated actions, carried out by rational men,<ref>{{cite book|title=American Assassins: The Darker Side of Politics|publisher=Princeton University Press|author=Clarke, J. W.|year=1982}}</ref> not all such attacks have been undertaken for political reasons.<ref>''E.g.'', [http://www.answers.com/topic/assassinations-presidential Assassinations, presidential] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304081350/http://www.answers.com/topic/assassinations-presidential|date=March 4, 2016}}. Answers.com. Retrieved February 23, 2010.</ref> Some attackers had questionable mental stability, and a few were judged legally insane.<ref>''E.g.'', Ben Dennison, [http://www.cracked.com/article_16705_the-6-most-utterly-insane-attempts-to-kill-us-president.html \"The 6 Most Utterly Insane Attempts to Kill a US President\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209084405/http://www.cracked.com/article_16705_the-6-most-utterly-insane-attempts-to-kill-us-president.html|date=February 9, 2016}}, ''Cracked'', October 21, 2008. Retrieved February 23, 2010.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091123202446/http://tfninsider.org/2009/11/19/praying-for-god-to-kill-the-president/ \"Praying for God to Kill the President\"], ''TFN Insider'', Texas Freedom Network, Retrieved February 23, 2010.</ref> Since the [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]] has for more than a century been elected from the same political party as the president, the assassination of the president is unlikely to result in major policy changes. This may explain why political groups typically do not make such attacks.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Politics of Insanity: Law, Crime, and Human Responsibility|author=Lawrence Zelic Freedman|journal=Political Psychology|volume=4|issue=1|date=March 1983|pages=171\u2013178|jstor=3791182|doi=10.2307/3791182}}</ref>\n\n==Presidents assassinated==\n===Abraham Lincoln===\n{{main|Assassination of Abraham Lincoln}}\n[[File:Lincoln assassination slide c1900 - Restoration.jpg|thumb|alt=Image of Lincoln being shot by Booth while sitting in a theater booth.|Shown in the presidential booth of Ford's Theatre, from left to right, are assassin [[John Wilkes Booth]], [[Abraham Lincoln]], [[Mary Todd Lincoln]], [[Clara Harris]], and [[Henry Rathbone]]]]\n\nThe assassination of [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Abraham Lincoln]] took place on [[Good Friday]], April 14, 1865, at [[Ford's Theatre]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], at approximately 10:15&nbsp;p.m. The assassin, [[John Wilkes Booth]], was a well-known actor and a Confederate sympathizer from Maryland; though he never joined the Confederate Army, he had contacts with the Confederate secret service.<ref>Donald (1996), pp. 586\u2013587.</ref> In 1864, Booth formulated a plan (very similar to one of Thomas N. Conrad previously authorized by the Confederacy)<ref>Donald (1996), p. 587.</ref> to kidnap Lincoln in exchange for the release of Confederate prisoners. After attending an April 11, 1865, speech in which Lincoln promoted voting rights for blacks, Booth decided to assassinate the President.<ref>Harrison (2000), pp. 3\u20134.</ref> Learning that the president would be attending [[Ford's Theatre]], Booth formulated a plan with co-conspirators to assassinate Lincoln at the theater, as well as [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Andrew Johnson]] and [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[William H. Seward]] at their homes. Lincoln attended the play ''[[Our American Cousin]]'' at Ford's Theatre.<ref>Donald (1996), pp. 594\u2013597.</ref> As the president sat in his state box in the balcony, watching the play, with his wife, [[Mary Todd Lincoln]], and two guests, Major [[Henry Rathbone]] and his fianc\u00e9e [[Clara Harris]], Booth entered from behind, aimed a .44 caliber Derringer pistol at the back of Lincoln's head, and fired, mortally wounding him. Rathbone momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped. An unconscious Lincoln was taken across the street to the [[Petersen House]]. After remaining in a [[coma]] for nine hours, Lincoln died at 7:22&nbsp;a.m. on April 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/alhtml/alrintr.html |title=Lincoln Papers: Lincoln Assassination: Introduction |publisher=Memory.loc.gov |accessdate=October 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005205326/http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/alhtml/alrintr.html |archivedate=October 5, 2013 }}</ref> As he died his breathing grew quieter, his face more calm.<ref>{{cite book |author=Tarbell, Ida Minerva |title=The Life of Abraham Lincoln |volume=4 |pages=40 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TDhpaY4aHYC&pg=RA1-PA34#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher= |date= |accessdate= |year=1920 }}</ref> According to some accounts, at his last drawn breath, on the morning after the assassination, he smiled broadly and then expired.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fox|first1=Richard|title=Lincoln's Body: A Cultural History|date=2015|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=0393247244}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-tls.co.uk/articles/private/with-a-smile-on-his-face/|title=With a smile on his face|first=Adam|last=Smith|date=July 8, 2015|publisher=|via=content.The Times Literary Supplement.co.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"backstoryradio.org\">{{cite web|title=Now He Belongs to the Ages - BackStory with the American History Guys|url=https://www.backstoryradio.org/shows/now-he-belongs-to-the-ages/|quote=Abraham Lincoln died, according to press reports, with a smile on his face. \u201cI had never seen upon the president's face an expression more genial and pleasings,\u201d wrote a New York Times reporter.}}</ref><ref name=\"Abel4\">{{cite book|last1=Abel|first1=E. Lawrence|title=A Finger in Lincoln's Brain: What Modern Science Reveals about Lincoln, His Assassination, and Its Aftermath|date=2015|publisher=ABC-CLIO|at= Chapter 14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=President Lincoln's Thoughts on April 14, 1865|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?324113-2/discussion-president-lincolns-thoughts-april-14-1865|quote=When he finally gave up the struggle for life at 7:22 A.M., his face was fixed in a smile, according to one bedside witness, treasury official, a smile that seemed almost an effort of life. Lincoln has passed on smoothly and contentedly, his facial expression suggesting that inner peace that prevailed as his final state of mind.}}</ref> Historians, most notably author Lee Davis have emphasized Lincoln's peaceful appearance when and after he died: \"It was the first time in four years, probably, that a peaceful expression crossed his face.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Assassinations That Changed The World'', History Channel</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Fox|first1=Richard|title=Lincoln's Body: A Cultural History |date=2015|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=0393247244}}</ref> Field wrote in a letter to ''[[The New York Times]]'': \"that there was 'no apparent suffering, no convulsive action, no rattling of the throat...[only] a mere cessation of breathing'... I had never seen upon the President's face an expression more genial and pleasing.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1865/04/17/news/our-great-loss-assassination-president-lincolndetails-fearful-crimeclosing.html|title=OUR GREAT LOSS; The Assassination of President Lincoln.DETAILS OF THE FEARFUL CRIME.Closing Moments and Death of the President.Probable Recovery of Secretary Seward. Rumors of the Arrest of the Assassins.The Funeral of President Lincoln to Take Place Next Wednesday. Expressions of Deep Sorrow Through-out the Land. OFFICIAL DISPATCHES. THE ASSASSINATION. Further Details of the Murder Narrow Recape of Secretary Stanton Measures Taken is Prevent the Escape of the Assassin of the President. LAST MOMENTS OF THE PRESIDENT. Interesting Letter from Maunsell B. Field Esq. THE GREAT CALAMITY |date=April 17, 1865|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018NOW HE BELONGS TO THE AGES\u2019 ABRAHAM LINCOLN'S ASSASSINATION|url=https://www.backstoryradio.org/shows/now-he-belongs-to-the-ages/|quote=Abraham Lincoln died, according to press reports, with a smile on his face. \u201cI had never seen upon the president\u2019s face an expression more genial and pleasing,\u201d wrote a New York Times reporter.}}</ref> The President's secretary, [[John Hay]], saw \"a look of unspeakable peace came upon his worn features\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Hay|first=John|title=The Life and Letters of John Hay Volume 1 (quote's original source is Hay's diary which is quoted in \"Abraham Lincoln: A History\", Volume 10, Page 292 by John G. Nicolay and John Hay)|date=1915|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Company|url=https://archive.org/stream/lifeandlettersof007751mbp/lifeandlettersof007751mbp_djvu.txt}}</ref>\n\nBeyond Lincoln's death, the plot failed: Seward was only wounded and Johnson's would-be attacker did not follow through. After being on the run for 12 days, Booth was tracked down and found on April 26, 1865 by Union soldiers on a farm in Virginia, some {{convert|70|mi|km}} south of Washington. After refusing to surrender, Booth was fatally shot by Union cavalryman [[Boston Corbett]]. The bullet struck Booth in the back of the head behind his left ear, passed though his neck, and out into the barn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/films/assassination/ |title=American Experience &#124; The Assassination of Abraham Lincoln |publisher=PBS |accessdate=December 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Martelle|first1=Scott|title=The Madman and the Assassin: The Strange Life of Boston Corbett, the Man Who Killed John Wilkes Booth|date=2015|publisher=Chicago Review Press|page=103}}</ref> A low scream of pain like that produced by a sudden throttling came from the assassin, and he pitched headlong to the floor.<ref>{{cite book|title=Terry Alford, Fortune\u2019s Fool: The Life of John Wilkes Booth}}</ref> Corbett and the other soldiers would note a sense of poetic, or cosmic, justice in that Lincoln and Booth were each shot around the same spot of the head.<ref>{{harvnb|Goodrich|2005|pp=227\u2013228}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Death of John Wilkes Booth, 1865|url=http://www.eyewitnesstohistory.com/booth.htm|publisher=Eyewitness to History/Ibis Communications|accessdate=August 16, 2012|quote=the bullet struck Booth in the back of the head, about an inch below the spot where his shot had entered the head of Mr. Lincoln.}}</ref> And the damage to Booth was no less severe than that to Lincoln: the bullet had pierced three [[vertebrae]] and partially severed his [[spinal cord]], [[paralysis|paralyzing]] him.<ref name=\"Goodrich, p. 211\">Goodrich, p. 211.</ref><ref name=Smith210>Smith, pp. 210\u2013213.</ref> Their conditions were different as well, as [[Mary C. Ames|Mary Clemmer Ames]] summed it up, \"The balls entered the skull of each at nearly the same spot, but the trilling difference made an immeasurable difference in the sufferings of the two. Mr. Lincoln was unconscious of all pain, while his assassin suffered as exquisite agony as if he had been broken on a wheel.\"<ref name=\"Clemmer\">[https://archive.org/details/tenyearsinwashi03clemgoog Clemmer, Mary. ''Ten Years in Washington: Life and Scenes in the National Capital as a Woman Sees Them.''] Cincinnati: Queen City Publishing Company, 1874.</ref> A soldier poured water into his mouth, which he immediately spat out, unable to swallow. The bullet wound prevented him from swallowing any of the liquid. In a weak voice, Booth asked for water and Conger and Baker gave it to him.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Martelle|first1=Scott|title=The Madman and the Assassin: The Strange Life of Boston Corbett, the Man Who Killed John Wilkes Booth|date=2015|publisher=Chicago Review Press|page=104}}</ref> He asked them to roll him over and turn him facedown. Conger thought it a bad idea. Then at least turn me on my side, the assassin pleaded. They did, but Conger saw that the move did not relieve Booth's suffering. Baker noticed it, too: \"He seemed to suffer extreme pain whenever he was moved...and would several times repeat, \u2018Kill me.\u2019\"<ref>Swanson, p. 139.</ref> At sunrise, Booth remained in agonising pain. His pulse weakening as his breathing became more laboured and irregular. In agony, unable to move his limbs, he asked a soldier to lift his hands before his face and whispered as he gazed at them, \"Useless ... Useless.\" These were his last words. A few minutes later, Booth began gasping for air as his throat continued to swell, then there was a shiver and a gurgle and his body shuddered, before Booth died from asphyxia - he literally choked to death. He died two hours after Corbett shot him. Corbett was initially arrested for disobeying orders, but was later released and was largely considered a hero by the media and the public. Four other conspirators were later hanged for their roles in the conspiracy.\n\n===James A. Garfield===\n[[File:Garfield assassination engraving cropped.jpg|thumb|alt=A black-and-white drawing of a crowd of people, some of whom are angry, the two foremost of whom are bearded and wearing top hats|President Garfield with [[James G. Blaine]] after being shot by [[Charles J. Guiteau]]]]\n{{main|Assassination of James A. Garfield}}\nThe assassination of [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[James A. Garfield]] began at the [[Baltimore and Potomac Railroad Station]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], at 9:30&nbsp;a.m. on Saturday, July 2, 1881, less than four months after he took office. As the president was arriving at the train station, writer and lawyer [[Charles J. Guiteau]] shot him twice with a [[.442 Webley]] British Bulldog revolver; one bullet grazed the president's shoulder, and the other pierced his back.<ref>{{harvp|Millard|2011|pp=189, 312}}</ref> For the next eleven weeks, Garfield endured [[medical malpractice]] and died on September 19, 1881 at 10:35&nbsp;p.m., of complications caused by infections, which were contracted by the doctors' relentless probing of his wound with unsterilized fingers and instruments.\n\nGuiteau was immediately arrested. After a highly publicized trial lasting from November 14, 1881 to January 25, 1882, he was found guilty and sentenced to death. A subsequent appeal was rejected, and he was executed by [[hanging]] on June 30, 1882 in the [[District of Columbia]], two days before the first anniversary of the shooting. Guiteau was assessed during his trial as mentally unbalanced and possibly suffered from some kind of [[bipolar disorder]] or from the effects of [[syphilis]] on the brain. He claimed to have shot Garfield out of disappointment for being passed over for appointment as [[United States Ambassador to France|Ambassador to France]]. He attributed the president's victory in the election to a speech he wrote in support of Garfield.<ref>{{cite book|last=Peskin|first=Allan|title=Garfield|url=https://archive.org/details/garfieldbiograph0000pesk|url-access=registration|year=1978|publisher=Kent State University Press|isbn=0-87338-210-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/garfieldbiograph0000pesk/page/587 587]}}</ref>\n\n===William McKinley===\n[[File:McKinleyAssassination.jpg|thumb|alt=A black-and-white drawing of a crowd of people, one of whom is being watched by all the others, all standing under a draped banner|[[Leon Czolgosz]] shoots [[president of the United States|President]] [[William McKinley|McKinley]] with a concealed revolver. Clipping of a wash drawing by T. Dart Walker.]]\n{{main|Assassination of William McKinley}}\nThe assassination of [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[William McKinley]] took place at 4:07&nbsp;p.m. on Friday, September 6, 1901, at the [[Temple of Music]] in [[Buffalo, New York]]. McKinley, attending the Pan-American Exposition, was shot twice in the abdomen at close range by [[Leon Czolgosz]], an [[anarchist]], who was armed with a .32 caliber revolver that was concealed underneath a handkerchief. The first bullet ricocheted off either a button or an award medal on McKinley's jacket and lodged in his sleeve; the second shot pierced his stomach. Although McKinley initially appeared to be recovering, his condition rapidly declined due to [[gangrene]] setting in around his wounds and he died on September 14, 1901 at 2:15&nbsp;a.m.\n\nMembers of the crowd, started by [[James Benjamin Parker]], subdued and captured Czolgosz. Afterward, the 4th Brigade, National Guard Signal Corps, and police intervened, beating Czolgosz so severely it was initially thought he might not live to stand trial. On September 24, after a rushed, two-day trial in state court, in which the defendant refused to defend himself, Czolgosz was easily convicted and later sentenced to death. He was executed by the [[electric chair]] in [[Auburn Prison]] on October 29. Czolgosz's actions were politically motivated, although it remains unclear what outcome, if any, he believed the shooting would yield.\n\nFollowing President McKinley's assassination, [[United States Congress|Congress]] directed the [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] to protect the president of the United States as part of its mandate.\n\n===John F. Kennedy===\n[[File:JFK limousine.png|thumb|JFK, Jackie, and the Connallys in the presidential limousine minutes before the [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy|assassination]]]]\n{{main|Assassination of John F. Kennedy}}\nThe assassination of [[President of the United States|United States president]] [[John F. Kennedy]] took place at 12:30&nbsp;p.m. (18:30 [[UTC]]) on Friday, November 22, 1963, in [[Dallas]], [[Texas]], during a presidential motorcade in [[Dealey Plaza]].{{sfn|Stokes|1979|pp=21}} Kennedy was riding with his wife [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis|Jacqueline]], [[Texas Governor]] [[John Connally]], and Connally's wife, [[Nellie Connally|Nellie]] when he was fatally shot. He was shot once in the back, the bullet exiting via his throat, and once in the head.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcadams.posc.mu.edu/press.htm|title=Doctors attending to Kennedy reported.|accessdate=May 15, 2018|date=November 1963}}</ref> Governor Connally was seriously wounded, and bystander [[James Tague]] received a minor facial injury from a small piece of curbstone that had fragmented after it was struck by one of the bullets. The motorcade rushed to [[Parkland Memorial Hospital]], where President Kennedy was pronounced dead at 1:00&nbsp;p.m. Former [[United States Marine Corps|U.S. Marine]] and [[Marxism|Marxist]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/lee-harvey-oswald-9430309|title=Lee Harvey Oswald|website=Biography.com|language=en-us|access-date=June 26, 2017}}</ref> [[Lee Harvey Oswald]], an order filler at the [[Texas School Book Depository]] from which the shots were fired, was arrested by the [[Dallas Police Department]] for the murder of Dallas policeman [[J. D. Tippit]], who was shot dead in a residential neighborhood in the Oak Cliff section of Dallas. Oswald was charged with both crimes shortly after his arrest. On Sunday, November 24, 1963, while being transferred from the city jail to the county jail, Oswald was fatally shot in the basement of Dallas Police Headquarters by Dallas nightclub owner [[Jack Ruby]]. Ruby was convicted of Oswald's murder, even though it was later overturned on appeal. In 1967, Ruby died in prison while awaiting a new trial.\n\nIn September 1964, the [[Warren Commission]] concluded that Kennedy and Tippit were both killed by Oswald, that Oswald had acted entirely alone in both murders, and that Ruby had acted alone in killing Oswald. Nonetheless, polls conducted from 1966 to 2004 found that up to 80% of Americans surveyed have suspected that there was a plot or [[cover-up]] to kill President Kennedy.<ref name=\"langer20031116\">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/images/pdf/937a1JFKAssassination.pdf |author=Gary Langer |title=John F. Kennedy's Assassination Leaves a Legacy of Suspicion |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=November 16, 2003 |accessdate=May 16, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110126060733/http://abcnews.go.com/images/pdf/937a1JFKAssassination.pdf |archivedate=January 26, 2011 }}</ref><ref>Jarrett Murphy, [http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/11/20/national/main584668.shtml \"40 Years Later: Who Killed JFK?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117235233/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/11/20/national/main584668.shtml |date=November 17, 2011 }}, [[CBS News]], November 21, 2003.</ref> Doubts and [[John F. Kennedy assassination conspiracy theories|conspiracy theories]] persist to the present.\n\n==Assassination attempts and plots==\n===Andrew Jackson===\n[[File:JacksonAssassinationAttempt.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Illustration of [[Andrew Jackson|Jackson's]] attempted assassination]]\nJanuary 30, 1835: Just outside the [[United States Capitol|Capitol Building]], a house painter named [[Richard Lawrence (failed assassin)|Richard Lawrence]] attempted to shoot [[Andrew Jackson|Jackson]] with two pistols, both of which misfired. Lawrence was apprehended after Jackson beat him severely with his cane. Lawrence was found [[Insanity defense|not guilty by reason of insanity]] and confined to a mental institution until his death in 1861.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/people/articles/web/20070130-richard-lawrence-andrew-jackson-assassination-warren-r-davis.shtml |title=Trying to Assassinate President Jackson |magazine=[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]] |date=January 30, 2007 |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024234731/http://www.americanheritage.com/people/articles/web/20070130-richard-lawrence-andrew-jackson-assassination-warren-r-davis.shtml |archivedate=October 24, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Abraham Lincoln===\nFebruary 23, 1861: The [[Baltimore Plot]] was an alleged conspiracy to assassinate [[President-elect]] [[Abraham Lincoln]] en route to his [[inauguration]]. [[Allan Pinkerton]]'s [[Pinkerton National Detective Agency|National Detective Agency]] played a key role in protecting the president-elect by managing Lincoln's security throughout the journey. Although scholars debate whether the threat was real, Lincoln and his advisers took actions to ensure his safe passage through Baltimore.\n\nAugust 1864: A lone rifle shot fired by an unknown sniper missed Lincoln's head by inches (passing through his hat) as he rode in the late evening, unguarded, north from the White House three miles (5&nbsp;km) to the [[President Lincoln's Cottage at the Soldiers' Home|Soldiers' Home]] (his regular retreat where he would work and sleep before returning to the White House the following morning). Near 11:00&nbsp;p.m., Private John W. Nichols of the [[150th Pennsylvania Infantry Regiment|Pennsylvania 150th Volunteers]], the sentry on duty at the gated entrance to the Soldiers' Home grounds, heard the rifle shot and moments later saw the president riding toward him \"bareheaded\". Lincoln described the matter to [[Ward Hill Lamon|Ward Lamon]], his old friend and loyal bodyguard.<ref>Flood, Charles Bracelen (2010). ''1864: Lincoln at the Gates of History''. Simon & Schuster Lincoln Library. {{ISBN|1416552286}}. pp. 266\u2013267.</ref><ref>Sandburg, Carl (1954). ''Abraham Lincoln: The Prairie Years and the War Years One-Volume Edition''. Harcourt. pp. 599\u2013600. {{ISBN|0-15-602611-2}}.</ref>\n\n===William Howard Taft===\n[[File:Presidents_Taft_and_Diaz,_Oct._1909.jpg|thumb|[[William Taft]] and [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]], historic first presidential summit, [[Ciudad Juarez]], [[Mexico]], October 16, 1909.]]\nIn 1909, [[William Howard Taft]] and [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]] planned a summit in [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]], Texas, and [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]], Mexico, a historic first meeting between a U.S. president and a Mexican president and also the first time an American president would cross the border into [[Mexico]].<ref>[[#Harris|Harris 2009]], p. 1.</ref> D\u00edaz requested the meeting to show U.S. support for his planned eighth run as president, and Taft agreed to support D\u00edaz in order to protect the several billion dollars of American capital then invested in Mexico.<ref>[[#Harris|Harris 2009]], p. 2.</ref> Both sides agreed that the disputed [[Chamizal dispute|Chamizal strip]] connecting El Paso to Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez would be considered neutral territory with no flags present during the summit, but the meeting focused attention on this territory and resulted in assassination threats and other serious security concerns.<ref>[[#Harris|Harris 2009]], p. 14.</ref> The [[Texas Ranger Division|Texas Rangers]], 4,000 U.S. and Mexican troops, U.S. Secret Service agents, [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] agents, and [[United States Marshals Service|U.S. Marshals]] were all called in to provide security.<ref>[[#Harris|Harris 2009]], p. 15.</ref> An additional 250 private security detail led by [[Frederick Russell Burnham]], the celebrated scout, was hired by [[John Hays Hammond]]. Hammond was a close friend of Taft from [[Yale University|Yale]] and a former candidate for U.S. vice president in 1908 who, along with his business partner Burnham, held considerable mining interests in Mexico.<ref>[[#Hampton|Hampton 1910]]</ref><ref>[[#vanWyk|van Wyk 2003]], pp. 440\u2013446.</ref><ref>{{cite news | date = October 16, 1909 | title = Mr. Taft's Peril; Reported Plot to Kill Two Presidents | newspaper= [[Daily Mail]] | location = London | issn = 0307-7578}}</ref> On October 16, the day of the summit, Burnham and Private C.R. Moore, a Texas Ranger, discovered a man holding a concealed [[Protector Palm Pistol|palm pistol]] standing at the El Paso Chamber of Commerce building along the procession route.<ref>[[#Hammond|Hammond 1935]], pp. 565-66.</ref> Burnham and Moore captured and disarmed the would-be assassin within only a few feet of Taft and D\u00edaz.<ref>[[#Harris|Harris 2009]], p. 213.</ref>\n\n===Theodore Roosevelt===\nThree and a half years after he left office, [[Theodore Roosevelt]] was running for president as a member of the [[Progressive Party (United States, 1912)|Progressive Party]].  While campaigning in [[Milwaukee|Milwaukee, Wisconsin]] on October 14, 1912, [[John Flammang Schrank]], a saloon-keeper from New York who had been stalking him for weeks, shot Roosevelt once in the chest with a [[.38 Special|.38-caliber]] [[Colt Police Positive Special]].  The 50-page text of his campaign speech titled \"[[wikisource:Progressive Cause Greater Than Any Individual|Progressive Cause Greater Than Any Individual]]\", folded over twice in Roosevelt's breast pocket, and a metal glasses case slowed the bullet, saving his life.  Schrank was immediately disarmed, captured, and might have been lynched had Roosevelt not shouted for Schrank to remain unharmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/videos/the-bull-moose#the-bull-moose |title=The Bull Moose and related media |accessdate=March 8, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308145415/http://www.history.com/videos/the-bull-moose#the-bull-moose |archivedate=March 8, 2010 }}</ref>  Roosevelt assured the crowd he was all right, then ordered police to take charge of Schrank and to make sure no violence was done to him.<ref name=\"remey\">{{cite book |first1=Oliver E. |last1=Remey |first2= Henry F. |last2=Cochems |first3=Wheeler P. |last3=Bloodgood |title=The Attempted Assassination of Ex-President Theodore Roosevelt |publisher=The Progressive Publishing Company |location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin |year=1912 |page=192 |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/21261}}</ref>\n\nRoosevelt, as an experienced hunter and anatomist, correctly concluded that since he was not coughing blood, the bullet had not reached his lung, and he declined suggestions to go to the hospital immediately.  Instead, he delivered his scheduled speech with blood seeping into his shirt.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.doctorzebra.com/prez/z_x26a_g.htm |title= Medical History of American Presidents |publisher= Doctor Zebra | accessdate= September 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>John Gurda. ''Cream City Chronicles: Stories of Milwaukee's Past''. Madison: Wisconsin Historical Society Press, 2016, pp. 189-191.</ref>  He spoke for 90 minutes before completing his speech and accepting medical attention.  His opening comments to the gathered crowd were, \"Ladies and gentlemen, I don't know whether you fully understand that I have just been shot, but it takes more than that to kill a Bull Moose.\"<ref>{{Citation | contribution-url = http://www.historybuff.com/library/refteddy.html | contribution = Excerpt | title = [[Detroit Free Press]] | publisher = History buff}}.{{dead link|date=April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"speech\">{{cite web |url=http://www.theodoreroosevelt.org/site/c.elKSIdOWIiJ8H/b.9297449/k.861A/It_Takes_More_Than_That_to_Kill_a_Bull_Moose_The_Leader_and_The_Cause.htm |title=It Takes More Than That to Kill a Bull Moose: The Leader and The Cause |publisher=Theodore Roosevelt Association |accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://theodoreroosevelt.org/research/speech%20kill%20moose.htm |title=Home - Theodore Roosevelt Association |publisher=Theodoreroosevelt.org |date=February 1, 2013 |accessdate=October 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129204515/http://www.theodoreroosevelt.org/research/speech%20kill%20moose.htm |archivedate=January 29, 2013 }}</ref>  Afterwards, probes and an x-ray showed that the bullet had lodged in Roosevelt's chest muscle, but did not penetrate the [[pulmonary pleurae]].  Doctors concluded that it would be less dangerous to leave it in place than to attempt to remove it, and Roosevelt carried the bullet with him for the rest of his life.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.theodoreroosevelt.org/life/timeline.htm |title=Roosevelt Timeline |publisher=Theodore Roosevelt | accessdate =September 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.theodoreroosevelt.org/life/timeline.htm Timeline of Theodore Roosevelt's Life by the Theodore Roosevelt Association<!-- bot-generated title -->] at www.theodoreroosevelt.org</ref>  He spent two weeks recuperating before returning to the campaign trail.  Despite his tenacity, Roosevelt ultimately lost his bid for reelection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-10-12/news/34393389_1_bull-moose-theodore-roosevelt-san-juan-hill |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130041100/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-10-12/news/34393389_1_bull-moose-theodore-roosevelt-san-juan-hill |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 30, 2013 |title=Justice Story: Teddy Roosevelt survives assassin when bullet hits folded speech in his pocket |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York |accessdate=October 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt Schrank's trial, the would-be assassin claimed that [[William McKinley]] had visited him in a dream and told him to avenge [[assassination of William McKinley|his assassination]] by killing Roosevelt.  He was found [[legally insane]] and was institutionalized until his death in 1943.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://webarchiveproject.org/26540/ |title=John Schrank |publisher=Classic Wisconsin |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420233653/http://webarchiveproject.org/26540/ |archivedate=April 20, 2016  }}</ref>\n\n===Herbert Hoover===\nOn November 19, 1928,<ref name=LifeHH>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0SDIAAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=fighting+quaker#v=onepage&q=Good%20will%20tour|last=Jeansonne|first=Glen|title=The Life of Herbert Hoover: Fighting Quaker, 1928-1933|year=2012|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=New York|pages=44\u201345|isbn=978-1-137-34673-5|accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref> President-elect [[Herbert Hoover|Hoover]] embarked on a ten-nation \"goodwill tour\" of [[Central America|Central]] and [[South America]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://history.state.gov/departmenthistory/travels/president/hoover-herbert-c |title=Travels of President Herbert C. Hoover |publisher=U.S. Department of State Office of the Historian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308031606/https://history.state.gov/departmenthistory/travels/president/hoover-herbert-c |archivedate=March 8, 2016 |access-date=February 5, 2016  }}</ref> While crossing the [[Andes]] mountains from [[Chile]], an assassination plot by [[Argentines|Argentine]] anarchists was thwarted. The group was led by [[Severino Di Giovanni]], who planned to blow up his train as it crossed the Argentinian [[Pampas|central plain]]. The plotters had an itinerary but the bomber was arrested before he could place the explosives on the rails. Hoover professed unconcern, tearing off the front page of a newspaper that revealed the plot and explaining, \"It's just as well that [[Lou Henry Hoover|Lou]] shouldn't see it,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hoover.archives.gov/exhibits/Hooverstory/gallery05/ |title=The Museum Exhibit Galleries, Gallery 5: The Logical Candidate, The President-Elect |publisher=Herbert Hoover Presidential Library and Museum |location=West Branch, Iowa |accessdate=February 24, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306153100/http://hoover.archives.gov/exhibits/Hooverstory/gallery05/ |archivedate=March 6, 2016  }}</ref> referring to his wife. His complimentary remarks on Argentina were well received in both the host country and in the press.<ref>{{cite news|title=National Affairs: Hoover Progress |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,929076,00.html |work=Time |date=December 24, 1928 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624161230/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C929076%2C00.html |archivedate=June 24, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Franklin D. Roosevelt===\nOn February 15, 1933, seventeen days before Roosevelt's [[First inauguration of Franklin D. Roosevelt|first presidential inauguration]], [[Giuseppe Zangara]] fired five shots at [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Roosevelt]] \nin [[Miami, Florida]]. Zangara did not wound the president-elect, but [[Chicago]] mayor [[Anton Cermak]] was killed and five other people wounded. Zangara pleaded guilty to the murder of Cermak and was executed in the electric chair on March 20, 1933. It has never been conclusively determined who was Zangara's target, and most assumed at first that he had been shooting at the president-elect. Another theory is that the attempt may have been ordered by the imprisoned [[Al Capone]], and that Cermak, who had led a crackdown on the [[Chicago Outfit]] and Chicago organized crime more generally, was the true target.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.graveyards.com/IL/Cook/bohemian/cermak.html |title=Bohemian National Cemetery: Mayor Anton Cermak |website=www.graveyards.com |accessdate=June 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809033530/http://www.graveyards.com/IL/Cook/bohemian/cermak.html |archivedate=August 9, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.crimelibrary.com/gangsters_outlaws/mob_bosses/giancana/guard_4.html|title= Sam 'Momo' Giancana - Live and Die by the Sword|publisher= [[Crime Library]]|accessdate= May 7, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070208170403/http://www.crimelibrary.com/gangsters_outlaws/mob_bosses/giancana/guard_4.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate =February 8, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Soviet Union|Soviet]] authorities claimed to have discovered a German plan to assassinate Roosevelt at the [[Teheran Conference|Tehran Conference]] in 1943.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mayle|first1=Paul D.|title=Eureka Summit: Agreement in Principle and the Big Three at Tehran, 1943|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JJtfSJrtPlAC|publisher=University of Delaware Press|publication-date=1987|page=57|isbn=9780874132953|accessdate=March 27, 2016| quote=[...] the Russians had uncovered a plot - German agents in Tehran had learned of Roosevelt's presence and were making plans for acion that was likely to take the form of an assassination attempt on one or more of the Big Three while they were in transit between meetings.}}</ref>\n\n===Harry S. Truman===\n{{main|Attempted assassination of Harry S. Truman}}\nMid-1947: During the pending of the independence of [[Israel]], the Zionist [[Stern Gang]] was believed to have sent a number of letter bombs addressed to the president and high-ranking staff at the White House. The Secret Service had been alerted by British intelligence after similar letters had been sent to high-ranking British officials and the Gang claimed credit. The mail room of the White House intercepted the letters and the Secret Service defused them. At the time, the incident was not publicized. Truman's daughter [[Margaret Truman]] confirmed the incident in her biography of Truman published in 1972. It had earlier been told in a memoir by Ira R.T. Smith, who worked in the mail room.<ref name=\"AP\">[https://archive.is/20130111013038/http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1951&dat=19721201&id=s00xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AeIFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2264,343939 AP, \"Jews Sent Truman Letter Bombs, Book Tells\"], ''Tri-City Herald'', December 1, 1972, accessed December 11, 2012</ref>\n\nNovember 1, 1950: Two [[Puerto Rico|Puerto Rican]] [[Puerto Rican independence movement|pro-independence activists]], [[Oscar Collazo]] and [[Griselio Torresola]], attempted to kill President [[Harry S Truman|Truman]] at the [[Blair House]], where Truman was living while the White House was undergoing some renovations. In the attack, Torresola mortally wounded [[White House Police Force|White House Policeman]] [[Leslie Coffelt]], who killed the attacker with a shot to the head. Torresola also wounded White House Policeman Joseph Downs. Collazo wounded another officer, and survived with serious injuries. Truman was not harmed, but he was placed at a huge risk. He commuted Collazo's death sentence after conviction in a federal trial to life in prison. In 1979, President [[Jimmy Carter]] commuted it to time served.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hibbits |first=Bernard |title=Presidential Pardons |url=http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/pardons6.htm |work=Jurist: The Legal Education Network |publisher=University of Pittsburgh School of Law |accessdate=December 16, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117201528/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/pardons6.htm |archivedate=November 17, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===John F. Kennedy===\nDecember 11, 1960: While vacationing in [[Palm Beach, Florida]], President-elect [[John F. Kennedy]] was threatened by [[Richard Paul Pavlick]], a 73-year-old former postal worker driven by hatred of Catholics. Pavlick intended to crash his [[dynamite]]-laden 1950 [[Buick]] into Kennedy's vehicle, but he changed his mind after seeing Kennedy's wife and daughter bid him goodbye.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://toledoblade.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20031121/NEWS08/111210127 |title=Kennedy presidency almost ended before he was inaugurated |work=[[The Blade (Toledo)|The Blade]] |location=Toledo, Ohio |date=November 21, 2003 |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930030120/http://toledoblade.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20031121%2FNEWS08%2F111210127 |archivedate=September 30, 2007 }}</ref> Pavlick was arrested three days later by the Secret Service after being stopped for a driving violation; police found the dynamite in his car and arrested him. On January 27, 1961, Pavlick was committed to the [[United States Public Health Service]] [[mental hospital]] in [[Springfield, Missouri]], then was indicted for threatening Kennedy's life seven weeks later. Charges against Pavlick were dropped on December 2, 1963, ten days after [[John F. Kennedy assassination|Kennedy's assassination in Dallas]].<ref name=postman>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M9_BSXV_s_4C&pg=PA164&dq=richard+paul+pavlick#v=onepage&q=richard%20paul%20pavlick|isbn=9780313364754|title=Killing the President: Assassinations, Attempts, and Rumored Attempts on U.S. Commanders-in-Chief: Assassinations, Attempts, and Rumored Attempts on U.S. Commanders-in-Chief|last1=Oliver|first1=Willard|last2=Marion|first2=Nancy E.|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2010}}</ref> Judge [[Emett Clay Choate]] ruled that Pavlick was unable to distinguish between right and wrong in his actions, but kept him in the mental hospital. The federal government also dropped charges in August 1964, and Pavlick was eventually released from the [[New Hampshire State Hospital]] on December 13, 1966.<ref name=postman/><ref name=children>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nxDyGK-iLiYC&pg=PA48&dq=richard+paul+pavlick#v=onepage&q=richard%20paul%20pavlick|isbn=9781581129847|title=The Fine Art of Executive Protection: Handbook for the Executive Protection Officer|last=Hunsicker|first=A.|publisher=Universal-Publishers|year=2007}}</ref><ref name=rpp>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3UXhAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA89&dq=richard+paul+pavlick#v=onepage&q=richard%20paul%20pavlick|isbn=9781134713257|title=John F. Kennedy|last=Ling|first=Peter J.|publisher=Routledge|year=2013}}</ref>\n\n===Richard Nixon===\nApril 13, 1972: [[Arthur Bremer]] carried a firearm to an event intending to shoot Nixon, but was put off by strong security.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} A few weeks later, he instead shot and seriously injured the Governor of [[Alabama]], [[George Wallace]], who was [[Paralysis|paralyzed]] until his death in 1998. Three other people were unintentionally wounded. Bremer served 35 years in prison for the shooting of Governor Wallace.<ref>{{cite web|title=Man Who Shot George Wallace To Be Freed|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/man-who-shot-george-wallace-to-be-freed-23-08-2007/|website=CBS|accessdate=September 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFebruary 22, 1974: [[Samuel Byck]] planned to kill [[Richard Nixon|Nixon]] by crashing a commercial airliner into the [[White House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.9-11commission.gov/report/911Report_Notes.htm |title=9/11 report notes |publisher=[[9/11 Commission]] |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412190717/http://www.9-11commission.gov/report/911Report_Notes.htm |archivedate=April 12, 2016 }}</ref> He [[Aircraft hijacking|hijacked the plane]] on the ground by force after killing a police officer, and was told that it could not take off with the wheel blocks still in place. After he shot both pilots (one later died), an officer named Charles 'Butch' Troyer shot Byck through the plane's door window. He survived long enough to kill himself by shooting.\n\n===Gerald Ford===\n{{main|Gerald Ford assassination attempt in Sacramento|Gerald Ford assassination attempt in San Francisco}}\nSeptember 5, 1975: On the northern grounds of the [[California State Capitol]], [[Lynette Fromme|Lynette \"Squeaky\" Fromme]], a follower of [[Charles Manson]], drew a [[Colt M1911]] .45 caliber pistol on [[Gerald R. Ford|Ford]] when he reached to shake her hand in a crowd. She had four cartridges in the pistol's [[Magazine (firearm)|magazine]] but none in the firing chamber, and as a result, the gun did not fire. She was quickly restrained by Secret Service agent [[Larry Buendorf]]. Fromme was sentenced to life in prison, but was released from custody on August 14, 2009 (two years and eight months after Ford's death in 2006).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/tdih.do?id=5322&action=tdihArticleCategory |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090502134729/http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history.do?id=5322&action=tdihArticleCategory |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 2, 2009 |title=1975 : Ford assassination attempt thwarted |publisher=[[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]] |accessdate=May 6, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nSeptember 22, 1975: In [[San Francisco, California]], only 17 days after Fromme's attempt, [[Sara Jane Moore]] fired a revolver at Ford from 40 feet (12&nbsp;m) away.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/president-ford-survives-second-assassination-attempt|title=1975: President Ford survives second assassination attempt|publisher=History Channel|accessdate=May 8, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106064815/https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/president-ford-survives-second-assassination-attempt|archive-date=January 6, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> A bystander, [[Oliver Sipple]], grabbed Moore's arm and the shot missed Ford, striking a building wall and slightly injuring taxi driver John Ludwig.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randomhouse.com/features/americancentury/imperialpres.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990422154905/http://www.randomhouse.com/features/americancentury/imperialpres.html|archivedate=April 22, 1999|title=The Imperial Presidency 1972-1980|accessdate=May 8, 2007}}</ref> Moore was tried and convicted in federal court, and sentenced to prison for life. She was paroled from a federal prison on December 31, 2007 after serving more than 30 years, one year and five days after Ford's natural death.\n\n===Jimmy Carter===\n[[Raymond Lee Harvey]] was an Ohio-born unemployed American [[Drifter (person)|drifter]]. He was arrested by the [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] after being found carrying a [[starter pistol]] with [[Blank (cartridge)|blank]] rounds, ten minutes before [[Jimmy Carter|Carter]] was to give a speech at the [[Civic Center, Los Angeles, California|Civic Center Mall]] in [[Los Angeles]] on May 5, 1979. Harvey had a history of [[mental illness]],<ref name=\"Time\">[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,920351,00.html \"Skid Row Plot: A scheme to kill Carter?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823095355/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C920351%2C00.html |date=August 23, 2013 }}, ''Time'' May 21, 1979.</ref> but police had to investigate his claim that he was part of a four-man operation to assassinate the president.<ref>\"The Plot to Kill Carter\", ''Newsweek'' May 21, 1979.</ref> According to Harvey, he fired seven blank rounds from the starter pistol on the hotel roof on the night of May 4 to test how much noise it would make. He claimed to have been with one of the plotters that night, whom he knew as \"Julio\". (This man was later identified as a 21-year-old illegal immigrant from Mexico, who gave the name Osvaldo Espinoza Ortiz.)<ref name=\"Time\" /> At the time of his arrest, Harvey had eight spent rounds in his pocket, as well as 70 unspent blank rounds for the gun.<ref name=\"STH\">\"Alleged Carter death plot: man charged\", ''The Sydney Morning Herald'' May 10, 1979.</ref> Harvey was jailed on a $50,000 bond, given his [[Transient laborer|transient]] status, and Ortiz was alternately reported as being held on a $100,000 bond as a [[material witness]]<ref name=\"Time\" /> or held on a $50,000 bond being charged with burglary from a car.<ref name=\"STH\" /> Charges against the pair were ultimately dismissed for a lack of evidence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=264078 |title=Harvey / \"Carter Assassination Plot\", CBS News broadcast |website=Vanderbilt Television News Archive |accessdate=June 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303225619/http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=264078 |archivedate=March 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n[[John Hinckley Jr.]] came close to shooting Carter during his re-election campaign, but he lost his nerve. He would later attempt to kill President Ronald Reagan in March 1981.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Hinckley Jr.: Hunting Carter and Reagan |url=https://www.historyonthenet.com/john-hinckley-jr/ |website=History on the Net |accessdate=August 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Taubman |first1=Philip |title=Investigators Think Hinckley Stalked Carter |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/04/12/us/investigators-think-hinckley-stalked-carter.html |accessdate=August 26, 2018 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Ronald Reagan===\n{{main|Attempted assassination of Ronald Reagan}}\n[[File: President Ronald Reagan moments before he was shot in an assassination attempt 1981.jpg|thumb|[[Ronald Reagan]] waves just before he is shot outside a Washington hotel on March 30, 1981. From left are [[Jerry Parr]], in white trench coat, who pushed Reagan into the limousine; [[press secretary]] [[James Brady]], who was seriously wounded by a gunshot wound to the head; Reagan; aide [[Michael Deaver]]; an unidentified policeman; policeman [[Thomas Delahanty|Thomas K. Delahanty]], who was shot in the neck; and secret service agent [[Timothy J. McCarthy|Tim McCarthy]], who was shot in the stomach.]]\nMarch 30, 1981: As [[Ronald Reagan]] returned to his [[Presidential state car (United States)|limousine]] after speaking at the [[Washington Hilton]] hotel, he and three others were struck by gunfire from would-be assassin [[John Hinckley Jr.]] Reagan was seriously wounded by a bullet that ricocheted off the side of the presidential limousine and hit him in the left underarm, breaking a rib, puncturing a lung, and causing serious internal bleeding. Although \"close to death\" upon arrival at [[George Washington University Hospital]], Reagan was stabilized in the emergency room, then underwent emergency exploratory surgery.<ref name=\"cnn transcript\">{{cite news|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0103/30/lkl.00.html|title=Remembering the Assassination Attempt on Ronald Reagan|date=March 30, 2001|accessdate=December 19, 2007|publisher=CNN}}</ref> He recovered and was released from the hospital on April 11.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/comment/dsouza200406080824.asp|work=National Review|accessdate=February 16, 2009|date=June 8, 2004|title=Purpose|author=[[Dinesh D'Souza|D'Souza, Dinesh]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203070233/http://nationalreview.com/comment/dsouza200406080824.asp <!-- Added by H3llBot -->|archivedate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> Besides Reagan, [[White House Press Secretary|White House press secretary]] [[James Brady]], Secret Service agent [[Tim McCarthy]], and police officer [[Thomas Delahanty]] were also wounded. All three survived, but Brady suffered brain damage and was permanently disabled; Brady's death in 2014 was considered homicide because it was ultimately caused by this injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/james-bradys-death-ruled-homicide-by-dc-medical-examiner/2014/08/08/686de224-1f41-11e4-82f9-2cd6fa8da5c4_story.html |title=Medical examiner rules James Brady's death a homicide |website=Washington Post |accessdate=June 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328024710/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/james-bradys-death-ruled-homicide-by-dc-medical-examiner/2014/08/08/686de224-1f41-11e4-82f9-2cd6fa8da5c4_story.html |archivedate=March 28, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nHinckley was immediately arrested, and later said he had wanted to kill Reagan to impress actress [[Jodie Foster]]. He was deemed mentally ill and confined to an institution. Hinckley was released from institutional psychiatric care on September 10, 2016.<ref name=\"foxnews.com\">{{cite news|title=John Hinckley Jr. to begin living full-time in Virginia Sept. 10|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/john-hinckley-jr-leaves-dc-mental-hospital-for-virginia|accessdate=December 6, 2018|agency=[[Fox News]]|date=September 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===George H. W. Bush===\nApril 13, 1993: According to Kuwaiti authorities, fourteen Kuwaiti and Iraqi men believed to be working for [[Saddam Hussein]] smuggled bombs into [[Kuwait]], planning to assassinate former president [[George H. W. Bush|Bush]] by a car bomb during his visit to [[Kuwait University]] three months after he had left office (in January 1993).<ref>{{Cite news|title=U.S. Strikes Iraq for Plot to Kill Bush|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/inatl/longterm/iraq/timeline/062793.htm|date=Jun 27, 1993|first=David|last=Von Drehle|work=[[The Washington Post]]|first2=R. Jeffrey|last2=Smith|lastauthoramp=yes|accessdate=February 14, 2011}}</ref> Kuwaiti officials claimed to have foiled the alleged plot and arrested the suspected assassins. Two of the suspects, Wali Abdelhadi Ghazali and Raad Abdel-Amir al-Assadi, retracted their confessions at the trial, claiming that they were coerced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fas.org/irp/agency/doj/oig/fbilab1/05bush2.htm |title=The Bush assassination attempt |publisher=[[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]]/[[FBI Laboratory]] report |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070402200736/http://www.fas.org/irp/agency/doj/oig/fbilab1/05bush2.htm |archivedate=April 2, 2007 }}</ref> Then-president [[Bill Clinton]] responded by launching a [[1993 cruise missile strikes on Iraq|cruise missile attack on an Iraqi intelligence building]] in [[Baghdad]].  The plot was used as one of the justifications for the [[Iraq Resolution]].\n\nAn analysis by the CIA's Counter-Terrorism Center concludes the assassination plot was likely fabricated by Kuwaiti authorities.<ref>{{cite news|title=CIA SAYS IRAQI PLOT TO KILL BUSH MAY BE FICTION|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1993-05-27-9305270298-story.html|date=May 27, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\n===Bill Clinton===\n*January 21, 1994: Ronald Gene Barbour, a retired military officer and freelance writer, plotted to kill Clinton while the president was jogging. Barbour returned to Florida a week later without having fired the shots at the president, who was on a state visit to [[Russia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/02/19/us/unemployed-man-is-charged-with-threat-to-kill-president.html |title=Unemployed Man Is Charged With Threat to Kill President |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 19, 1994 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517033656/http://www.nytimes.com/1994/02/19/us/unemployed-man-is-charged-with-threat-to-kill-president.html |archivedate=May 17, 2017 }}</ref> Barbour was sentenced to five years in prison and was released in 1998.\n*September 12, 1994: [[Frank Eugene Corder]] flew a stolen single-engine [[Cessna]] onto the White House lawn and crashed into a tree. Corder, a truck driver from Maryland who reportedly had alcohol problems, allegedly tried to hit the White House. He was killed in the crash. The president and first family were not home at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9903E1D6173BF930A2575AC0A962958260 |title=Crash at the White House: The Overview |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 14, 1994 |accessdate=August 27, 2008 |first=Maureen |last=Dowd |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124161827/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9903E1D6173BF930A2575AC0A962958260 |archivedate=January 24, 2009 }}</ref>\n*October 29, 1994: [[Francisco Martin Duran]] fired at least 29 shots with a semiautomatic rifle at the White House from a fence overlooking the north lawn, thinking that [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]] was among the men in dark suits standing there (Clinton was inside). Three tourists, Harry Rakosky, Ken Davis and Robert Haines, tackled Duran before he could injure anyone. Found to have a [[suicide]] note in his pocket, Duran was sentenced to 40 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prop1.org/park/pave/rev6.htm |title=Summary Statement of Facts (The September 12, 1994 Plane Crash and The October 29, 1994 Shooting) Background Information on the White House Security Review |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927212928/http://prop1.org/park/pave/rev6.htm |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n*1996: During his visit to the [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation]] (APEC) forum in Manila, Clinton's motorcade was rerouted before it was to drive over a bridge. Service officers had intercepted a message suggesting that an attack was imminent, and [[Lewis Merletti]], the director of the Secret Service, ordered the motorcade to be re-routed. An intelligence team later discovered a bomb under the bridge. Subsequent U.S. investigation \"revealed that [the plot] was masterminded by a Saudi terrorist living in Afghanistan named [[Osama bin Laden]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/philippines/6867331/Osama-bin-Laden-came-within-minutes-of-killing-Bill-Clinton.html |title=Osama bin Laden came within minutes of killing Bill Clinton |last=Leonard |first=Tom |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=December 22, 2009 |accessdate=June 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091225150252/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/philippines/6867331/Osama-bin-Laden-came-within-minutes-of-killing-Bill-Clinton.html |archivedate=December 25, 2009 }}</ref>\n*October 2018: A package containing a [[pipe bomb]] addressed to wife [[Hillary Clinton]] and sent to their home in [[Chappaqua, New York]] was intercepted by Secret Service. It was [[October 2018 United States mail bombing attempts|one of several mailed to other Democratic leaders in the same week]], including former president [[Barack Obama]].<ref name=cnn>[https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/24/politics/bill-clinton-hillary-clinton-chappaqua/index.html 'Act of terror': Bombs sent to CNN, Clintons, Obamas, Holder] CNN, October 24, 2018</ref> [[Bill Clinton]] was at the Chappaqua home when the package was intercepted, while Hillary was in Florida campaigning for Democrats.<ref>https://www.indystar.com/story/news/2018/10/24/bomb-found-home-hillary-and-bill-clinton-new-york-city-suburb/1748676002/</ref> Fingerprint DNA revealed that the package was sent by Florida resident Cesar Sayoc, who was captured two days after the package was intercepted.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/26/politics/suspicious-packages-arrest/index.html|title=Bomb suspect arrest: What we know about Cesar Sayoc|author1=Jason Hanna |author2=Evan Perez |author3=Scott Glover|work=CNN|access-date=October 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026165125/https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/26/politics/suspicious-packages-arrest/index.html|archive-date=October 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Prosecutors sought a life sentence for Sayoc, but due to the bombs being intentionally made not to go off the judge instead sentenced him to 20 years in prison.\n\n===George W. Bush===\n{{main|Assassination attempts against George W. Bush}}\nFebruary 7, 2001: While President [[George W. Bush]] was in the White House, Robert Pickett, standing outside the perimeter fence, discharged a number of shots from a weapon in the direction of the White House. He was sentenced to three years in prison.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timelines.latimes.com/us-presidential-assassinations-and-attempts/ |title=U.S. presidential assassinations and attempts |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20131204011625/http://timelines.latimes.com/us-presidential-assassinations-and-attempts/ |archivedate=December 4, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nMay 10, 2005: While President Bush was giving a speech in the [[Freedom Square, Tbilisi|Freedom Square]] in [[Tbilisi]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Vladimir Arutyunian]] threw a live [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]-made [[RGD-5]] [[hand grenade]] toward the podium. The grenade had its pin pulled, but did not explode because a red tartan handkerchief was wrapped tightly around it, preventing the safety lever from detaching.<ref>[https://www.fbi.gov/page2/jan06/grenadeattack011106.htm US FBI report into the attack and investigation] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070411035739/http://www.fbi.gov/page2/jan06/grenadeattack011106.htm |date=April 11, 2007 }}.</ref> After escaping that day, Arutyunian was arrested in July 2005. During his arrest, he killed an Interior Ministry agent. He was convicted in January 2006 and given a [[life sentence]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/europe/01/11/georgia.grenade/index.html |title=Bush grenade attacker gets life |publisher=CNN |date=January 11, 2006 |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704105908/http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/europe/01/11/georgia.grenade/index.html |archivedate=July 4, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/page2/jan06/grenadeattack011106.htm|title=The case of the failed hand grenade attack|publisher=[[FBI]] Press Room|date=January 11, 2006|accessdate=May 6, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070411035739/http://www.fbi.gov/page2/jan06/grenadeattack011106.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate =April 11, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Barack Obama===\n{{main|Assassination threats against Barack Obama}}\n*April 2009: A plot to assassinate Obama at the [[Alliance of Civilizations]] summit in [[Istanbul]], Turkey was discovered after a man of Syrian origins carrying forged [[Al-Jazeera]] TV [[press credentials]] was found. The man confessed to the Turkish security services details of his plan to kill Obama with a knife with three alleged accomplices.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.edition.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/04/06/turkey.assassination.plot/index.html |title=Plot to assassinate Obama foiled in Turkey |work=CNN |author=Ed Henry |date=April 6, 2009 |accessdate=June 21, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703004736/http://www.edition.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/04/06/turkey.assassination.plot/index.html |archivedate=July 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n*November 2011: [[2011 White House shooting|Oscar Ramiro Ortega-Hernandez]] hit the White House with several rounds fired from a semi-automatic rifle. No one was injured. However, a window was broken.<ref name=Leonnig>{{cite news|title=Secret Service fumbled response after gunman hit White House residence in 2011 |last=Leonnig |first=Carol D. |date=September 27, 2014 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/secret-service-stumbled-after-gunman-hit-white-house-residence-in-2011/2014/09/27/d176b6ac-442a-11e4-b437-1a7368204804_story.html |accessdate=December 14, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108004003/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/secret-service-stumbled-after-gunman-hit-white-house-residence-in-2011/2014/09/27/d176b6ac-442a-11e4-b437-1a7368204804_story.html |archivedate=November 8, 2016 }}</ref> He was sentenced to 25 years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oscar Ramiro Ortega-Hernandez, man who shot at White House, gets 25 years |author=<!--Staff--> |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 31, 2014 |publisher=[[Fox News Channel]] |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/03/31/oscar-ramiro-ortega-hernandez-man-who-shot-at-white-house-gets-25-years/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150111232958/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/03/31/oscar-ramiro-ortega-hernandez-man-who-shot-at-white-house-gets-25-years/ |archivedate=January 11, 2015 |accessdate=March 10, 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n*April 2013: [[April 2013 ricin letters|Another attempt]] was made when a letter laced with [[ricin]], a deadly poison, was sent to President Obama.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/18/politics/tainted-letter-intercepted/index.html |title=FBI confirms letters to Obama, others contained ricin |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=October 14, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130825152537/http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/18/politics/tainted-letter-intercepted/index.html |archivedate=August 25, 2013 }}</ref>\n*October 2018: [[October 2018 United States mail bombing attempts|A package]] that contained a fabricated pipe bomb was sent to former president Obama at his home in Washington, D.C. The package was intercepted by [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Merrit |title=Apparent 'Pipe Bombs' Mailed To Clinton, Obama And CNN |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/10/24/660161491/u-s-intercepts-suspicious-packages-addressed-to-clinton-and-obama |accessdate=October 25, 2018 |work=NPR |date=October 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\"Potentially destructive devices\" sent to Clinton, Obama, CNN prompt massive response |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/live-news/suspicious-packages-pipe-bomb-clinton-obama-cnn-nyc-wasserman-schultz-office-live-updates/ |accessdate=October 25, 2018 |work=CBS News |date=October 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Donald Trump===\n{{main|Attempted assassination of Donald Trump}}\n*June 2016: [[Michael Steven Sandford]], a British national with a history of mental illness, tried to seize a police officer's pistol at a Trump rally in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], in an attempt to assassinate Trump (then the presumptive Republican nominee). Sandford had reportedly been planning such an action for over a year. The pistol caught in the holster and Sandford was immediately arrested, and eventually deported to the [[United Kingdom]]. The incident received less coverage in the United States than in Britain, where it led to a debate over the [[Mental Capacity Act 2005]] and was the subject of a BBC documentary.<ref name=\"Frizzell29January2017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/jan/27/brit-who-tried-kill-trump-michael-sandford-donald-bbc-president|title='He never even watched the news' \u2013 the Brit who tried to kill Trump|last=Frizzell|first=Nell|date=January 27, 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=January 29, 2017}}</ref>\n*November 2017: A man affiliated with the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] was arrested by the [[Philippine National Police]] in [[Rizal Park]] for reportedly planning to assassinate President Trump during the [[ASEAN Summit]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/how-the-secret-service-foiled-an-assassination-attempt-against-trump-by-isis? |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |title=How the Secret Service Foiled an Assassination Plot Against Trump by ISIS |first=Marlow |last=Stern |date=October 12, 2018}}</ref>\n*October 2018: William Clyde Allen III, a U.S. Navy veteran, sent a letter containing crushed [[Ricinus|castor beans]] to President Trump. The letter did not reach the White House as it was seized by the Secret Service. He sent similar letters to Secretary of Defense [[James Mattis]] and Chief of Naval Operations Adm. [[John M. Richardson (admiral)|John Richardson]]. Allen was arrested on October 3, 2018 in Utah.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barr |first1=Luke |title=Man accused of sending letters laced with ricin 'wanted to send a message' |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/man-accused-sending-letters-laced-ricin-wanted-send/story?id=58309953 |accessdate=October 9, 2018 |publisher=ABC News |date=October 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Whitehurst |first1=Lindsay |title=Authorities Arrest Navy Veteran in Connection With Suspicious Envelopes Sent to President Trump |url=http://time.com/5414790/utah-man-ricin-letter-trump-arrested/ |accessdate=October 9, 2018 |magazine=Time |date=October 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Copp |first1=Tara |title=Navy vet arrested for allegedly trying to poison Mattis and the Navy's top officer |url=https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2018/10/03/navy-vet-william-clyde-allen-iii-arrested-in-ricin-poison-case/ |accessdate=October 9, 2018 |publisher=Military Times |date=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Death rumored to be an assassination==\nIn June 1923, President [[Warren G. Harding]] set out on a cross-country \"Voyage of Understanding\", planning to meet with citizens and explain his policies. During this trip, he became the first president to visit [[Alaska]], which was then a U.S. [[Territory of Alaska|territory]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historytogo.utah.gov/utah_chapters/from_war_to_war/presidenthardings1923visittoutah.html|title=President Harding's 1923 Visit to Utah|last=Reeve|first=W. Paul|date=July 1995|work=History Blazer|access-date=June 14, 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150502040538/http://historytogo.utah.gov/utah_chapters/from_war_to_war/presidenthardings1923visittoutah.html|archive-date=May 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRumors of [[political corruption|corruption]] in the Harding administration were beginning to circulate in [[Washington, D.C.]], by 1923, and Harding was profoundly shocked by a long message he received while in Alaska, apparently detailing illegal activities by his own cabinet that were allegedly unknown to him. At the end of July, while traveling south from Alaska through [[British Columbia]], he developed what was thought to be a severe case of [[food poisoning]]. He gave the final speech of his life to a large crowd at the University of Washington Stadium (now [[Husky Stadium]]) at the [[University of Washington]] campus in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. A scheduled speech in [[Portland, Oregon]], was canceled. The president's train proceeded south to [[San Francisco]]. Upon arriving at the [[Palace Hotel, San Francisco|Palace Hotel]], he developed [[pneumonia]]. Harding died in his hotel room of either a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] or a [[stroke]] at 7:35&nbsp;p.m. (19:35) on August 2, 1923. The formal announcement, printed in ''[[The New York Times]]'' of that day, stated: \"A [[stroke]] of [[apoplexy]] was the cause of death.\" He had been ill exactly one week.<ref>{{cite news|title=Harding a Farm Boy Who Rose by Work |url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/1102.html |quote=Nominated for the Presidency as a compromise candidate and elected by a tremendous majority because of a reaction against the policies of his predecessor, Warren Gamaliel Harding, twenty-ninth President of the United States, owed his political elevation largely to his engaging personal traits, his ability to work in harmony with the leaders of his party, and the fact that he typified in himself the average prosperous American citizen. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=July 21, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015045948/http://nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/1102.html |archivedate=October 15, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n[[United States Navy|Naval]] physicians surmised that Harding had suffered a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]]. The Hardings' personal medical advisor, homeopath and [[Surgeon General of the United States|Surgeon General]] [[Charles E. Sawyer]], disagreed with the diagnosis. His wife, [[Florence Harding]], refused permission for an [[autopsy]], which soon led to speculation that the president had been the victim of a plot, possibly carried out by his wife, as Harding apparently had been unfaithful to the first lady. [[Gaston Means|Gaston B. Means]], an amateur historian and [[Gadfly (social)|gadfly]], noted in his book ''The Strange Death of President Harding'' (1930) that the circumstances surrounding his death led to suspicions that he had been poisoned. A number of individuals attached to him, both personally and politically, would have welcomed Harding's death, as they would have been disgraced in association by Means' assertion of Harding's \"imminent impeachment\".\n\n==See also==\n*[[Assassination of Robert F. Kennedy]], Democratic presidential candidate, on June 5, 1968\n*[[George Wallace#Democratic presidential primaries of 1972 and assassination attempt|Attempted assassination of George Wallace]], Democratic presidential candidate, on May 15, 1972\n*[[Thomas R. Marshall#Assassination attempt|Attempted assassination of Thomas R. Marshall]], vice president, on July 2, 1915\n*[[Curse of Tippecanoe]]\n*[[Kennedy curse]]\n*[[List of assassinated and executed heads of state and government]]\n*[[List of incidents of political violence in Washington, D.C.]]\n*[[List of White House security breaches]]\n*[[Threatening the President of the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |ref=Hammond |last=Hammond |first=John Hays |authorlink=John Hays Hammond |year=1935 |title=The Autobiography of John Hays Hammond |url=https://archive.org/details/autobiographyofj0001hamm |url-access=registration |location=New York |publisher=Farrar & Rinehart |isbn=978-0-405-05913-1 |oclc=867910}} Free at the Internet Archive: [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.60381/page/n9 Volume 1] and [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.179915/page/n7 Volume 2].\n* {{cite magazine |ref=Hampton |last=Hampton |first=Benjamin B. |date=April 1, 1910 |title=The Vast Riches of Alaska: Will the Morgan-Guggenheim Combination Acquire Them, or Will They Benefit the Whole People? |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R4BIAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA450-IA2#v=twopage&q&f=false |magazine=Hampton's Magazine |volume=24 |issue=1 |pages=451\u2013468}}\n* {{cite book |ref=Harris |last1=Harris |first1=Charles H., III |last2=Sadler |first2=Louis R. |year=2009 |title=The Secret War in El Paso: Mexican Revolutionary Intrigue, 1906\u20131920 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4UYzDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=twopage&q&f=false |location=Albuquerque, N.M. |publisher=University of New Mexico Press |isbn=9780826346520 |oclc=762600819}}\n* {{cite book |ref=vanWyk |last=van Wyk |first=Peter |year=2003 |title=Burnham: King of Scouts |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iOXmRapkttoC&printsec=frontcover#v=twopage&q&f=false |location=Victoria, B.C., Canada |publisher=Trafford Publishing |isbn=978-1-4120-0901-0 |oclc=52799114}}\n\n{{US Presidential Assassinations}}\n{{Lists of US Presidents and Vice Presidents}}\n\n[[Category:Assassinations of Presidents of the United States| ]]\n[[Category:Attempted assassinations of Presidents of the United States| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of assassinations|United States]]\n[[Category:Lists of criminals|Assassination attempts, U.S. Presidents]]\n[[Category:Lists of events in the United States|Presidential assassination attempts and plots]]\n[[Category:Lists relating to the United States presidency|Assassination attempts]]\n[[Category:United States crime-related lists|Assassination attempts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\nAssassination attempts and plots on the [[president of the United States]] have been numerous, ranging from the early 19th century to the 2010s. More than 30 attempts to kill an [[incumbent]] or former president, or a [[President-elect of the United States|president-elect]] have been made since the early 19th century. Four sitting presidents have been killed: [[Abraham Lincoln]] (1865), [[James A. Garfield]] (1881), [[William McKinley]] (1901), and [[John F. Kennedy]] (1963). Additionally, two presidents have been injured in attempted assassinations: [[Theodore Roosevelt]] (1912; former president at the time) and [[Ronald Reagan]] (1981). In all of these cases, the attack weapon used was a firearm. \n\nAlthough historian James W. Clarke has suggested that most American assassinations were politically motivated actions, carried out by rational men,<ref>{{cite book|title=American Assassins: The Darker Side of Politics|publisher=Princeton University Press|author=Clarke, J. W.|year=1982}}</ref> not all such attacks have been undertaken for political reasons.<ref>''E.g.'', [http://www.answers.com/topic/assassinations-presidential Assassinations, presidential] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304081350/http://www.answers.com/topic/assassinations-presidential|date=March 4, 2016}}. Answers.com. Retrieved February 23, 2010.</ref> Some attackers had questionable mental stability, and a few were judged legally insane.<ref>''E.g.'', Ben Dennison, [http://www.cracked.com/article_16705_the-6-most-utterly-insane-attempts-to-kill-us-president.html \"The 6 Most Utterly Insane Attempts to Kill a US President\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209084405/http://www.cracked.com/article_16705_the-6-most-utterly-insane-attempts-to-kill-us-president.html|date=February 9, 2016}}, ''Cracked'', October 21, 2008. Retrieved February 23, 2010.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091123202446/http://tfninsider.org/2009/11/19/praying-for-god-to-kill-the-president/ \"Praying for God to Kill the President\"], ''TFN Insider'', Texas Freedom Network, Retrieved February 23, 2010.</ref> Since the [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]] has for more than a century been elected from the same political party as the president, the assassination of the president is unlikely to result in major policy changes. This may explain why political groups typically do not make such attacks.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Politics of Insanity: Law, Crime, and Human Responsibility|author=Lawrence Zelic Freedman|journal=Political Psychology|volume=4|issue=1|date=March 1983|pages=171\u2013178|jstor=3791182|doi=10.2307/3791182}}</ref>\n\n==Presidents assassinated==\n===Abraham Lincoln===\n{{main|Assassination of Abraham Lincoln}}\n[[File:Lincoln assassination slide c1900 - Restoration.jpg|thumb|alt=Image of Lincoln being shot by Booth while sitting in a theater booth.|Shown in the presidential booth of Ford's Theatre, from left to right, are assassin [[John Wilkes Booth]], [[Abraham Lincoln]], [[Mary Todd Lincoln]], [[Clara Harris]], and [[Henry Rathbone]]]]\n\nThe assassination of [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Abraham Lincoln]] took place on [[Good Friday]], April 14, 1865, at [[Ford's Theatre]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], at approximately 10:15&nbsp;p.m. The assassin, [[John Wilkes Booth]], was a well-known actor and a Confederate sympathizer from Maryland; though he never joined the Confederate Army, he had contacts with the Confederate secret service.<ref>Donald (1996), pp. 586\u2013587.</ref> In 1864, Booth formulated a plan (very similar to one of Thomas N. Conrad previously authorized by the Confederacy)<ref>Donald (1996), p. 587.</ref> to kidnap Lincoln in exchange for the release of Confederate prisoners. After attending an April 11, 1865, speech in which Lincoln promoted voting rights for blacks, Booth decided to assassinate the President.<ref>Harrison (2000), pp. 3\u20134.</ref> Learning that the president would be attending [[Ford's Theatre]], Booth formulated a plan with co-conspirators to assassinate Lincoln at the theater, as well as [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Andrew Johnson]] and [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[William H. Seward]] at their homes. Lincoln attended the play ''[[Our American Cousin]]'' at Ford's Theatre.<ref>Donald (1996), pp. 594\u2013597.</ref> As the president sat in his state box in the balcony, watching the play, with his wife, [[Mary Todd Lincoln]], and two guests, Major [[Henry Rathbone]] and his fianc\u00e9e [[Clara Harris]], Booth entered from behind, aimed a .44 caliber Derringer pistol at the back of Lincoln's head, and fired, mortally wounding him. Rathbone momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped. An unconscious Lincoln was taken across the street to the [[Petersen House]]. After remaining in a [[coma]] for nine hours, Lincoln died at 7:22&nbsp;a.m. on April 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/alhtml/alrintr.html |title=Lincoln Papers: Lincoln Assassination: Introduction |publisher=Memory.loc.gov |accessdate=October 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005205326/http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/alhtml/alrintr.html |archivedate=October 5, 2013 }}</ref> As he died his breathing grew quieter, his face more calm.<ref>{{cite book |author=Tarbell, Ida Minerva |title=The Life of Abraham Lincoln |volume=4 |pages=40 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TDhpaY4aHYC&pg=RA1-PA34#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher= |date= |accessdate= |year=1920 }}</ref> According to some accounts, at his last drawn breath, on the morning after the assassination, he smiled broadly and then expired.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fox|first1=Richard|title=Lincoln's Body: A Cultural History|date=2015|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=0393247244}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-tls.co.uk/articles/private/with-a-smile-on-his-face/|title=With a smile on his face|first=Adam|last=Smith|date=July 8, 2015|publisher=|via=content.The Times Literary Supplement.co.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"backstoryradio.org\">{{cite web|title=Now He Belongs to the Ages - BackStory with the American History Guys|url=https://www.backstoryradio.org/shows/now-he-belongs-to-the-ages/|quote=Abraham Lincoln died, according to press reports, with a smile on his face. \u201cI had never seen upon the president's face an expression more genial and pleasings,\u201d wrote a New York Times reporter.}}</ref><ref name=\"Abel4\">{{cite book|last1=Abel|first1=E. Lawrence|title=A Finger in Lincoln's Brain: What Modern Science Reveals about Lincoln, His Assassination, and Its Aftermath|date=2015|publisher=ABC-CLIO|at= Chapter 14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=President Lincoln's Thoughts on April 14, 1865|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?324113-2/discussion-president-lincolns-thoughts-april-14-1865|quote=When he finally gave up the struggle for life at 7:22 A.M., his face was fixed in a smile, according to one bedside witness, treasury official, a smile that seemed almost an effort of life. Lincoln has passed on smoothly and contentedly, his facial expression suggesting that inner peace that prevailed as his final state of mind.}}</ref> Historians, most notably author Lee Davis have emphasized Lincoln's peaceful appearance when and after he died: \"It was the first time in four years, probably, that a peaceful expression crossed his face.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Assassinations That Changed The World'', History Channel</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Fox|first1=Richard|title=Lincoln's Body: A Cultural History |date=2015|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=0393247244}}</ref> Field wrote in a letter to ''[[The New York Times]]'': \"that there was 'no apparent suffering, no convulsive action, no rattling of the throat...[only] a mere cessation of breathing'... I had never seen upon the President's face an expression more genial and pleasing.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1865/04/17/news/our-great-loss-assassination-president-lincolndetails-fearful-crimeclosing.html|title=OUR GREAT LOSS; The Assassination of President Lincoln.DETAILS OF THE FEARFUL CRIME.Closing Moments and Death of the President.Probable Recovery of Secretary Seward. Rumors of the Arrest of the Assassins.The Funeral of President Lincoln to Take Place Next Wednesday. Expressions of Deep Sorrow Through-out the Land. OFFICIAL DISPATCHES. THE ASSASSINATION. Further Details of the Murder Narrow Recape of Secretary Stanton Measures Taken is Prevent the Escape of the Assassin of the President. LAST MOMENTS OF THE PRESIDENT. Interesting Letter from Maunsell B. Field Esq. THE GREAT CALAMITY |date=April 17, 1865|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018NOW HE BELONGS TO THE AGES\u2019 ABRAHAM LINCOLN'S ASSASSINATION|url=https://www.backstoryradio.org/shows/now-he-belongs-to-the-ages/|quote=Abraham Lincoln died, according to press reports, with a smile on his face. \u201cI had never seen upon the president\u2019s face an expression more genial and pleasing,\u201d wrote a New York Times reporter.}}</ref> The President\u2019s secretary, [[John Hay]], saw \"a look of unspeakable peace came upon his worn features\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Hay|first=John|title=The Life and Letters of John Hay Volume 1 (quote's original source is Hay's diary which is quoted in \"Abraham Lincoln: A History\", Volume 10, Page 292 by John G. Nicolay and John Hay)|date=1915|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Company|url=https://archive.org/stream/lifeandlettersof007751mbp/lifeandlettersof007751mbp_djvu.txt}}</ref>\n\nBeyond Lincoln's death, the plot failed: Seward was only wounded and Johnson's would-be attacker did not follow through. After being on the run for 12 days, Booth was tracked down and found on April 26, 1865 by Union soldiers on a farm in Virginia, some {{convert|70|mi|km}} south of Washington. After refusing to surrender, Booth was fatally shot by Union cavalryman [[Boston Corbett]]. The bullet struck Booth in the back of the head behind his left ear, passed though his neck, and out into the barn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/films/assassination/ |title=American Experience &#124; The Assassination of Abraham Lincoln |publisher=PBS |accessdate=December 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Martelle|first1=Scott|title=The Madman and the Assassin: The Strange Life of Boston Corbett, the Man Who Killed John Wilkes Booth|date=2015|publisher=Chicago Review Press|page=103}}</ref> A low scream of pain like that produced by a sudden throttling came from the assassin, and he pitched headlong to the floor.<ref>{{cite book|title=Terry Alford, Fortune\u2019s Fool: The Life of John Wilkes Booth}}</ref> Corbett and the other soliders would note a sense of poetic, or cosmic, justice in that Lincoln and Booth were each shot around the same spot of the head.<ref>{{harvnb|Goodrich|2005|pp=227\u2013228}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Death of John Wilkes Booth, 1865|url=http://www.eyewitnesstohistory.com/booth.htm|publisher=Eyewitness to History/Ibis Communications|accessdate=August 16, 2012|quote=the bullet struck Booth in the back of the head, about an inch below the spot where his shot had entered the head of Mr. Lincoln.}}</ref> And the damage to Booth was no less severe than that to Lincoln: the bullet had pierced three [[vertebrae]] and partially severed his [[spinal cord]], [[paralysis|paralyzing]] him.<ref name=\"Goodrich, p. 211\">Goodrich, p. 211.</ref><ref name=Smith210>Smith, pp. 210\u2013213.</ref> Their conditions were different as well, as [[Mary C. Ames|Mary Clemmer Ames]] summed it up, \"The balls entered the skull of each at nearly the same spot, but the trilling difference made an immeasurable difference in the sufferings of the two. Mr. Lincoln was unconscious of all pain, while his assassin suffered as exquisite agony as if he had been broken on a wheel.\"<ref name=\"Clemmer\">[https://archive.org/details/tenyearsinwashi03clemgoog Clemmer, Mary. ''Ten Years in Washington: Life and Scenes in the National Capital as a Woman Sees Them.''] Cincinnati: Queen City Publishing Company, 1874.</ref> A soldier poured water into his mouth, which he immediately spat out, unable to swallow. The bullet wound prevented him from swallowing any of the liquid. In a weak voice, Booth asked for water and Conger and Baker gave it to him.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Martelle|first1=Scott|title=The Madman and the Assassin: The Strange Life of Boston Corbett, the Man Who Killed John Wilkes Booth|date=2015|publisher=Chicago Review Press|page=104}}</ref> He asked them to roll him over and turn him facedown. Conger thought it a bad idea. Then at least turn me on my side, the assassin pleaded. They did, but Conger saw that the move did not relieve Booth\u2019s suffering. Baker noticed it, too: \"He seemed to suffer extreme pain whenever he was moved...and would several times repeat, \u2018Kill me.\u2019\"<ref>Swanson, p. 139.</ref> At sunrise, Booth remained in agonising pain. His pulse weakening as his breathing became more laboured and irregular. In agony, unable to move his limbs, he asked a soldier to lift his hands before his face and whispered as he gazed at them, \"Useless ... Useless.\" These were his last words. A few minutes later, Booth began gasping for air as his throat continued to swell, then there was a shiver and a gurgle and his body shuddered, before Booth died from asphyxia - he literally choked to death. He died two hours after Corbett shot him. Corbett was initially arrested for disobeying orders, but was later released and was largely considered a hero by the media and the public. Four other conspirators were later hanged for their roles in the conspiracy.\n\n===James A. Garfield===\n[[File:Garfield assassination engraving cropped.jpg|thumb|alt=A black-and-white drawing of a crowd of people, some of whom are angry, the two foremost of whom are bearded and wearing top hats|President Garfield with [[James G. Blaine]] after being shot by [[Charles J. Guiteau]]]]\n{{main|Assassination of James A. Garfield}}\nThe assassination of [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[James A. Garfield]] began at the [[Baltimore and Potomac Railroad Station]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], at 9:30&nbsp;a.m. on Saturday, July 2, 1881, less than four months after he took office. As the president was arriving at the train station, writer and lawyer [[Charles J. Guiteau]] shot him twice with a [[.442 Webley]] British Bulldog revolver; one bullet grazed the president's shoulder, and the other pierced his back.<ref>{{harvp|Millard|2011|pp=189, 312}}</ref> For the next eleven weeks, Garfield endured [[medical malpractice]] and died on September 19, 1881 at 10:35&nbsp;p.m., of complications caused by infections, which were contracted by the doctors' relentless probing of his wound with unsterilized fingers and instruments. \n\nGuiteau was immediately arrested. After a highly publicized trial lasting from November 14, 1881 to January 25, 1882, he was found guilty and sentenced to death. A subsequent appeal was rejected, and he was executed by [[hanging]] on June 30, 1882 in the [[District of Columbia]], two days before the first anniversary of the shooting. Guiteau was assessed during his trial as mentally unbalanced and possibly suffered from some kind of [[bipolar disorder]] or from the effects of [[syphilis]] on the brain. He claimed to have shot Garfield out of disappointment for being passed over for appointment as [[United States Ambassador to France|Ambassador to France]]. He attributed the president's victory in the election to a speech he wrote in support of Garfield.<ref>{{cite book|last=Peskin|first=Allan|title=Garfield|url=https://archive.org/details/garfieldbiograph0000pesk|url-access=registration|year=1978|publisher=Kent State University Press|isbn=0-87338-210-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/garfieldbiograph0000pesk/page/587 587]}}</ref>\n\n===William McKinley===\n[[File:McKinleyAssassination.jpg|thumb|alt=A black-and-white drawing of a crowd of people, one of whom is being watched by all the others, all standing under a draped banner|[[Leon Czolgosz]] shoots [[president of the United States|President]] [[William McKinley|McKinley]] with a concealed revolver. Clipping of a wash drawing by T. Dart Walker.]]\n{{main|Assassination of William McKinley}}\nThe assassination of [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[William McKinley]] took place at 4:07&nbsp;p.m. on Friday, September 6, 1901, at the [[Temple of Music]] in [[Buffalo, New York]]. McKinley, attending the Pan-American Exposition, was shot twice in the abdomen at close range by [[Leon Czolgosz]], an [[anarchist]], who was armed with a .32 caliber revolver that was concealed underneath a handkerchief. The first bullet ricocheted off either a button or an award medal on McKinley's jacket and lodged in his sleeve; the second shot pierced his stomach. Although McKinley initially appeared to be recovering, his condition rapidly declined due to [[gangrene]] setting in around his wounds and he died on September 14, 1901 at 2:15&nbsp;a.m.\n\nMembers of the crowd, started by [[James Benjamin Parker]], subdued and captured Czolgosz. Afterward, the 4th Brigade, National Guard Signal Corps, and police intervened, beating Czolgosz so severely it was initially thought he might not live to stand trial. On September 24, after a rushed, two-day trial in state court, in which the defendant refused to defend himself, Czolgosz was easily convicted and later sentenced to death. He was executed by the [[electric chair]] in [[Auburn Prison]] on October 29. Czolgosz's actions were politically motivated, although it remains unclear what outcome, if any, he believed the shooting would yield.\n\nFollowing President McKinley's assassination, [[United States Congress|Congress]] directed the [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] to protect the president of the United States as part of its mandate.\n\n===John F. Kennedy===\n[[File:JFK limousine.png|thumb|JFK, Jackie, and the Connallys in the presidential limousine minutes before the [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy|assassination]]]]\n{{main|Assassination of John F. Kennedy}}\nThe assassination of [[President of the United States|United States president]] [[John F. Kennedy]] took place at 12:30&nbsp;p.m. (18:30 [[UTC]]) on Friday, November 22, 1963, in [[Dallas]], [[Texas]], during a presidential motorcade in [[Dealey Plaza]].{{sfn|Stokes|1979|pp=21}} Kennedy was riding with his wife [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis|Jacqueline]], [[Texas Governor]] [[John Connally]], and Connally's wife, [[Nellie Connally|Nellie]] when he was fatally shot. He was shot once in the back, the bullet exiting via his throat, and once in the head.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcadams.posc.mu.edu/press.htm|title=Doctors attending to Kennedy reported.|accessdate=May 15, 2018|date=November 1963}}</ref> Governor Connally was seriously wounded, and bystander [[James Tague]] received a minor facial injury from a small piece of curbstone that had fragmented after it was struck by one of the bullets. The motorcade rushed to [[Parkland Memorial Hospital]], where President Kennedy was pronounced dead at 1:00&nbsp;p.m. Former [[United States Marine Corps|U.S. Marine]] and [[Marxism|Marxist]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/lee-harvey-oswald-9430309|title=Lee Harvey Oswald|website=Biography.com|language=en-us|access-date=June 26, 2017}}</ref> [[Lee Harvey Oswald]], an order filler at the [[Texas School Book Depository]] from which the shots were fired, was arrested by the [[Dallas Police Department]] for the murder of Dallas policeman [[J. D. Tippit]], who was shot dead in a residential neighborhood in the Oak Cliff section of Dallas. Oswald was charged with both crimes shortly after his arrest. On Sunday, November 24, 1963, while being transferred from the city jail to the county jail, Oswald was fatally shot in the basement of Dallas Police Headquarters by Dallas nightclub owner [[Jack Ruby]]. Ruby was convicted of Oswald's murder, even though it was later overturned on appeal. In 1967, Ruby died in prison while awaiting a new trial.\n\nIn September 1964, the [[Warren Commission]] concluded that Kennedy and Tippit were both killed by Oswald, that Oswald had acted entirely alone in both murders, and that Ruby had acted alone in killing Oswald. Nonetheless, polls conducted from 1966 to 2004 found that up to 80% of Americans surveyed have suspected that there was a plot or [[cover-up]] to kill President Kennedy.<ref name=\"langer20031116\">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/images/pdf/937a1JFKAssassination.pdf |author=Gary Langer |title=John F. Kennedy's Assassination Leaves a Legacy of Suspicion |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=November 16, 2003 |accessdate=May 16, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110126060733/http://abcnews.go.com/images/pdf/937a1JFKAssassination.pdf |archivedate=January 26, 2011 }}</ref><ref>Jarrett Murphy, [http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/11/20/national/main584668.shtml \"40 Years Later: Who Killed JFK?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117235233/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/11/20/national/main584668.shtml |date=November 17, 2011 }}, [[CBS News]], November 21, 2003.</ref> Doubts and [[John F. Kennedy assassination conspiracy theories|conspiracy theories]] persist to the present.\n\n==Assassination attempts and plots==\n===Andrew Jackson===\n[[File:JacksonAssassinationAttempt.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Illustration of [[Andrew Jackson|Jackson's]] attempted assassination]]\nJanuary 30, 1835: Just outside the [[United States Capitol|Capitol Building]], a house painter named [[Richard Lawrence (failed assassin)|Richard Lawrence]] attempted to shoot [[Andrew Jackson|Jackson]] with two pistols, both of which misfired. Lawrence was apprehended after Jackson beat him severely with his cane. Lawrence was found [[Insanity defense|not guilty by reason of insanity]] and confined to a mental institution until his death in 1861.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/people/articles/web/20070130-richard-lawrence-andrew-jackson-assassination-warren-r-davis.shtml |title=Trying to Assassinate President Jackson |magazine=[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]] |date=January 30, 2007 |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024234731/http://www.americanheritage.com/people/articles/web/20070130-richard-lawrence-andrew-jackson-assassination-warren-r-davis.shtml |archivedate=October 24, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Abraham Lincoln===\nFebruary 23, 1861: The [[Baltimore Plot]] was an alleged conspiracy to assassinate [[President-elect]] [[Abraham Lincoln]] en route to his [[inauguration]]. [[Allan Pinkerton]]'s [[Pinkerton National Detective Agency|National Detective Agency]] played a key role in protecting the president-elect by managing Lincoln's security throughout the journey. Although scholars debate whether the threat was real, Lincoln and his advisers took actions to ensure his safe passage through Baltimore.\n\nAugust 1864: A lone rifle shot fired by an unknown sniper missed Lincoln's head by inches (passing through his hat) as he rode in the late evening, unguarded, north from the White House three miles (5&nbsp;km) to the [[President Lincoln's Cottage at the Soldiers' Home|Soldiers' Home]] (his regular retreat where he would work and sleep before returning to the White House the following morning). Near 11:00 p.m., Private John W. Nichols of the [[150th Pennsylvania Infantry Regiment|Pennsylvania 150th Volunteers]], the sentry on duty at the gated entrance to the Soldiers' Home grounds, heard the rifle shot and moments later saw the president riding toward him \"bareheaded\". Lincoln described the matter to [[Ward Hill Lamon|Ward Lamon]], his old friend and loyal bodyguard.<ref>Flood, Charles Bracelen (2010). ''1864: Lincoln at the Gates of History''. Simon & Schuster Lincoln Library. {{ISBN|1416552286}}. pp. 266\u2013267.</ref><ref>Sandburg, Carl (1954). ''Abraham Lincoln: The Prairie Years and the War Years One-Volume Edition''. Harcourt. pp. 599\u2013600. {{ISBN|0-15-602611-2}}.</ref>\n\n===William Howard Taft===\n[[File:Presidents_Taft_and_Diaz,_Oct._1909.jpg|thumb|[[William Taft]] and [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]], historic first presidential summit, [[Ciudad Juarez]], [[Mexico]], October 16, 1909.]]\nIn 1909, [[William Howard Taft]] and [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]] planned a summit in [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]], Texas, and [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]], Mexico, a historic first meeting between a U.S. president and a Mexican president and also the first time an American president would cross the border into [[Mexico]].<ref>[[#Harris|Harris 2009]], p. 1.</ref> D\u00edaz requested the meeting to show U.S. support for his planned eighth run as president, and Taft agreed to support D\u00edaz in order to protect the several billion dollars of American capital then invested in Mexico.<ref>[[#Harris|Harris 2009]], p. 2.</ref> Both sides agreed that the disputed [[Chamizal dispute|Chamizal strip]] connecting El Paso to Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez would be considered neutral territory with no flags present during the summit, but the meeting focused attention on this territory and resulted in assassination threats and other serious security concerns.<ref>[[#Harris|Harris 2009]], p. 14.</ref> The [[Texas Ranger Division|Texas Rangers]], 4,000 U.S. and Mexican troops, U.S. Secret Service agents, [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] agents, and [[United States Marshals Service|U.S. Marshals]] were all called in to provide security.<ref>[[#Harris|Harris 2009]], p. 15.</ref> An additional 250 private security detail led by [[Frederick Russell Burnham]], the celebrated scout, was hired by [[John Hays Hammond]]. Hammond was a close friend of Taft from [[Yale University|Yale]] and a former candidate for U.S. vice president in 1908 who, along with his business partner Burnham, held considerable mining interests in Mexico.<ref>[[#Hampton|Hampton 1910]]</ref><ref>[[#vanWyk|van Wyk 2003]], pp. 440\u2013446.</ref><ref>{{cite news | date = October 16, 1909 | title = Mr. Taft's Peril; Reported Plot to Kill Two Presidents | newspaper= [[Daily Mail]] | location = London | issn = 0307-7578}}</ref> On October 16, the day of the summit, Burnham and Private C.R. Moore, a Texas Ranger, discovered a man holding a concealed [[Protector Palm Pistol|palm pistol]] standing at the El Paso Chamber of Commerce building along the procession route.<ref>[[#Hammond|Hammond 1935]], pp. 565-66.</ref> Burnham and Moore captured and disarmed the would-be assassin within only a few feet of Taft and D\u00edaz.<ref>[[#Harris|Harris 2009]], p. 213.</ref>\n\n===Theodore Roosevelt===\nThree and a half years after he left office, [[Theodore Roosevelt]] was running for president as a member of the [[Progressive Party (United States, 1912)|Progressive Party]].  While campaigning in [[Milwaukee|Milwaukee, Wisconsin]] on October 14, 1912, [[John Flammang Schrank]], a saloon-keeper from New York who had been stalking him for weeks, shot Roosevelt once in the chest with a [[.38 Special|.38-caliber]] [[Colt Police Positive Special]].  The 50-page text of his campaign speech titled \"[[wikisource:Progressive Cause Greater Than Any Individual|Progressive Cause Greater Than Any Individual]]\", folded over twice in Roosevelt's breast pocket, and a metal glasses case slowed the bullet, saving his life.  Schrank was immediately disarmed, captured, and might have been lynched had Roosevelt not shouted for Schrank to remain unharmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/videos/the-bull-moose#the-bull-moose |title=The Bull Moose and related media |accessdate=March 8, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308145415/http://www.history.com/videos/the-bull-moose#the-bull-moose |archivedate=March 8, 2010 }}</ref>  Roosevelt assured the crowd he was all right, then ordered police to take charge of Schrank and to make sure no violence was done to him.<ref name=\"remey\">{{cite book |first1=Oliver E. |last1=Remey |first2= Henry F. |last2=Cochems |first3=Wheeler P. |last3=Bloodgood |title=The Attempted Assassination of Ex-President Theodore Roosevelt |publisher=The Progressive Publishing Company |location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin |year=1912 |page=192 |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/21261}}</ref>\n\nRoosevelt, as an experienced hunter and anatomist, correctly concluded that since he was not coughing blood, the bullet had not reached his lung, and he declined suggestions to go to the hospital immediately.  Instead, he delivered his scheduled speech with blood seeping into his shirt.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.doctorzebra.com/prez/z_x26a_g.htm |title= Medical History of American Presidents |publisher= Doctor Zebra | accessdate= September 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>John Gurda. ''Cream City Chronicles: Stories of Milwaukee's Past''. Madison: Wisconsin Historical Society Press, 2016, pp. 189-191.</ref>  He spoke for 90 minutes before completing his speech and accepting medical attention.  His opening comments to the gathered crowd were, \"Ladies and gentlemen, I don't know whether you fully understand that I have just been shot, but it takes more than that to kill a Bull Moose.\"<ref>{{Citation | contribution-url = http://www.historybuff.com/library/refteddy.html | contribution = Excerpt | title = [[Detroit Free Press]] | publisher = History buff}}.{{deadlink|date=April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"speech\">{{cite web |url=http://www.theodoreroosevelt.org/site/c.elKSIdOWIiJ8H/b.9297449/k.861A/It_Takes_More_Than_That_to_Kill_a_Bull_Moose_The_Leader_and_The_Cause.htm |title=It Takes More Than That to Kill a Bull Moose: The Leader and The Cause |publisher=Theodore Roosevelt Association |accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://theodoreroosevelt.org/research/speech%20kill%20moose.htm |title=Home - Theodore Roosevelt Association |publisher=Theodoreroosevelt.org |date=February 1, 2013 |accessdate=October 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129204515/http://www.theodoreroosevelt.org/research/speech%20kill%20moose.htm |archivedate=January 29, 2013 }}</ref>  Afterwards, probes and an x-ray showed that the bullet had lodged in Roosevelt's chest muscle, but did not penetrate the [[pulmonary pleurae]].  Doctors concluded that it would be less dangerous to leave it in place than to attempt to remove it, and Roosevelt carried the bullet with him for the rest of his life.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.theodoreroosevelt.org/life/timeline.htm |title=Roosevelt Timeline |publisher=Theodore Roosevelt | accessdate =September 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.theodoreroosevelt.org/life/timeline.htm Timeline of Theodore Roosevelt's Life by the Theodore Roosevelt Association<!-- bot-generated title -->] at www.theodoreroosevelt.org</ref>  He spent two weeks recuperating before returning to the campaign trail.  Despite his tenacity, Roosevelt ultimately lost his bid for reelection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-10-12/news/34393389_1_bull-moose-theodore-roosevelt-san-juan-hill |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130041100/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-10-12/news/34393389_1_bull-moose-theodore-roosevelt-san-juan-hill |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 30, 2013 |title=Justice Story: Teddy Roosevelt survives assassin when bullet hits folded speech in his pocket |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York |accessdate=October 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt Schrank's trial, the would-be assassin claimed that [[William McKinley]] had visited him in a dream and told him to avenge [[assassination of William McKinley|his assassination]] by killing Roosevelt.  He was found [[legally insane]] and was institutionalized until his death in 1943.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://webarchiveproject.org/26540/ |title=John Schrank |publisher=Classic Wisconsin |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420233653/http://webarchiveproject.org/26540/ |archivedate=April 20, 2016  }}</ref>\n\n===Herbert Hoover===\nOn November 19, 1928,<ref name=LifeHH>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0SDIAAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=fighting+quaker#v=onepage&q=Good%20will%20tour|last=Jeansonne|first=Glen|title=The Life of Herbert Hoover: Fighting Quaker, 1928-1933|year=2012|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=New York|pages=44\u201345|isbn=978-1-137-34673-5|accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref> President-elect [[Herbert Hoover|Hoover]] embarked on a ten-nation \"goodwill tour\" of [[Central America|Central]] and [[South America]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://history.state.gov/departmenthistory/travels/president/hoover-herbert-c |title=Travels of President Herbert C. Hoover |publisher=U.S. Department of State Office of the Historian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308031606/https://history.state.gov/departmenthistory/travels/president/hoover-herbert-c |archivedate=March 8, 2016 |access-date=February 5, 2016  }}</ref> While crossing the [[Andes]] mountains from [[Chile]], an assassination plot by [[Argentines|Argentine]] anarchists was thwarted. The group was led by [[Severino Di Giovanni]], who planned to blow up his train as it crossed the Argentinian [[Pampas|central plain]]. The plotters had an itinerary but the bomber was arrested before he could place the explosives on the rails. Hoover professed unconcern, tearing off the front page of a newspaper that revealed the plot and explaining, \"It's just as well that [[Lou Henry Hoover|Lou]] shouldn't see it,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hoover.archives.gov/exhibits/Hooverstory/gallery05/ |title=The Museum Exhibit Galleries, Gallery 5: The Logical Candidate, The President-Elect |publisher=Herbert Hoover Presidential Library and Museum |location=West Branch, Iowa |accessdate=February 24, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306153100/http://hoover.archives.gov/exhibits/Hooverstory/gallery05/ |archivedate=March 6, 2016  }}</ref> referring to his wife. His complimentary remarks on Argentina were well received in both the host country and in the press.<ref>{{cite news|title=National Affairs: Hoover Progress |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,929076,00.html |work=Time |date=December 24, 1928 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624161230/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C929076%2C00.html |archivedate=June 24, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Franklin D. Roosevelt===\nOn February 15, 1933, seventeen days before Roosevelt's [[First inauguration of Franklin D. Roosevelt|first presidential inauguration]], [[Giuseppe Zangara]] fired five shots at [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Roosevelt]] \nin [[Miami, Florida]]. Zangara did not wound the president-elect, but [[Chicago]] mayor [[Anton Cermak]] was killed and five other people wounded. Zangara pleaded guilty to the murder of Cermak and was executed in the electric chair on March 20, 1933. It has never been conclusively determined who was Zangara's target, and most assumed at first that he had been shooting at the president-elect. Another theory is that the attempt may have been ordered by the imprisoned [[Al Capone]], and that Cermak, who had led a crackdown on the [[Chicago Outfit]] and Chicago organized crime more generally, was the true target.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.graveyards.com/IL/Cook/bohemian/cermak.html |title=Bohemian National Cemetery: Mayor Anton Cermak |website=www.graveyards.com |accessdate=June 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809033530/http://www.graveyards.com/IL/Cook/bohemian/cermak.html |archivedate=August 9, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.crimelibrary.com/gangsters_outlaws/mob_bosses/giancana/guard_4.html|title= Sam 'Momo' Giancana - Live and Die by the Sword|publisher= [[Crime Library]]|accessdate= May 7, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070208170403/http://www.crimelibrary.com/gangsters_outlaws/mob_bosses/giancana/guard_4.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate =February 8, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Soviet Union|Soviet]] authorities claimed to have discovered a German plan to assassinate Roosevelt at the [[Teheran Conference|Tehran Conference]] in 1943.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mayle|first1=Paul D.|title=Eureka Summit: Agreement in Principle and the Big Three at Tehran, 1943|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JJtfSJrtPlAC|publisher=University of Delaware Press|publication-date=1987|page=57|isbn=9780874132953|accessdate=March 27, 2016| quote=[...] the Russians had uncovered a plot - German agents in Tehran had learned of Roosevelt's presence and were making plans for acion that was likely to take the form of an assassination attempt on one or more of the Big Three while they were in transit between meetings.}}</ref>\n\n===Harry S. Truman===\n{{main|Attempted assassination of Harry S. Truman}}\nMid-1947: During the pending of the independence of [[Israel]], the Zionist [[Stern Gang]] was believed to have sent a number of letter bombs addressed to the president and high-ranking staff at the White House. The Secret Service had been alerted by British intelligence after similar letters had been sent to high-ranking British officials and the Gang claimed credit. The mail room of the White House intercepted the letters and the Secret Service defused them. At the time, the incident was not publicized. Truman's daughter [[Margaret Truman]] confirmed the incident in her biography of Truman published in 1972. It had earlier been told in a memoir by Ira R.T. Smith, who worked in the mail room.<ref name=\"AP\">[https://archive.is/20130111013038/http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1951&dat=19721201&id=s00xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AeIFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2264,343939 AP, \"Jews Sent Truman Letter Bombs, Book Tells\"], ''Tri-City Herald'', December 1, 1972, accessed December 11, 2012</ref>\n\nNovember 1, 1950: Two [[Puerto Rico|Puerto Rican]] [[Puerto Rican independence movement|pro-independence activists]], [[Oscar Collazo]] and [[Griselio Torresola]], attempted to kill President [[Harry S Truman|Truman]] at the [[Blair House]], where Truman was living while the White House was undergoing some renovations. In the attack, Torresola mortally wounded [[White House Police Force|White House Policeman]] [[Leslie Coffelt]], who killed the attacker with a shot to the head. Torresola also wounded White House Policeman Joseph Downs. Collazo wounded another officer, and survived with serious injuries. Truman was not harmed, but he was placed at a huge risk. He commuted Collazo's death sentence after conviction in a federal trial to life in prison. In 1979, President [[Jimmy Carter]] commuted it to time served.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hibbits |first=Bernard |title=Presidential Pardons |url=http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/pardons6.htm |work=Jurist: The Legal Education Network |publisher=University of Pittsburgh School of Law |accessdate=December 16, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117201528/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/pardons6.htm |archivedate=November 17, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===John F. Kennedy===\nDecember 11, 1960: While vacationing in [[Palm Beach, Florida]], President-elect [[John F. Kennedy]] was threatened by [[Richard Paul Pavlick]], a 73-year-old former postal worker driven by hatred of Catholics. Pavlick intended to crash his [[dynamite]]-laden 1950 [[Buick]] into Kennedy's vehicle, but he changed his mind after seeing Kennedy's wife and daughter bid him goodbye.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://toledoblade.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20031121/NEWS08/111210127 |title=Kennedy presidency almost ended before he was inaugurated |work=[[The Blade (Toledo)|The Blade]] |location=Toledo, Ohio |date=November 21, 2003 |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930030120/http://toledoblade.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20031121%2FNEWS08%2F111210127 |archivedate=September 30, 2007 }}</ref> Pavlick was arrested three days later by the Secret Service after being stopped for a driving violation; police found the dynamite in his car and arrested him. On January 27, 1961, Pavlick was committed to the [[United States Public Health Service]] [[mental hospital]] in [[Springfield, Missouri]], then was indicted for threatening Kennedy's life seven weeks later. Charges against Pavlick were dropped on December 2, 1963, ten days after [[John F. Kennedy assassination|Kennedy's assassination in Dallas]].<ref name=postman>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M9_BSXV_s_4C&pg=PA164&dq=richard+paul+pavlick#v=onepage&q=richard%20paul%20pavlick|isbn=9780313364754|title=Killing the President: Assassinations, Attempts, and Rumored Attempts on U.S. Commanders-in-Chief: Assassinations, Attempts, and Rumored Attempts on U.S. Commanders-in-Chief|last1=Oliver|first1=Willard|last2=Marion|first2=Nancy E.|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2010}}</ref> Judge [[Emett Clay Choate]] ruled that Pavlick was unable to distinguish between right and wrong in his actions, but kept him in the mental hospital. The federal government also dropped charges in August 1964, and Pavlick was eventually released from the [[New Hampshire State Hospital]] on December 13, 1966.<ref name=postman/><ref name=children>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nxDyGK-iLiYC&pg=PA48&dq=richard+paul+pavlick#v=onepage&q=richard%20paul%20pavlick|isbn=9781581129847|title=The Fine Art of Executive Protection: Handbook for the Executive Protection Officer|last=Hunsicker|first=A.|publisher=Universal-Publishers|year=2007}}</ref><ref name=rpp>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3UXhAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA89&dq=richard+paul+pavlick#v=onepage&q=richard%20paul%20pavlick|isbn=9781134713257|title=John F. Kennedy|last=Ling|first=Peter J.|publisher=Routledge|year=2013}}</ref>\n\n===Richard Nixon===\nApril 13, 1972: [[Arthur Bremer]] carried a firearm to an event intending to shoot Nixon, but was put off by strong security.{{fact|date=April 2019}} A few weeks later, he instead shot and seriously injured the Governor of [[Alabama]], [[George Wallace]], who was [[Paralysis|paralyzed]] until his death in 1998. Three other people were unintentionally wounded. Bremer served 35 years in prison for the shooting of Governor Wallace.<ref>{{cite web|title=Man Who Shot George Wallace To Be Freed|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/man-who-shot-george-wallace-to-be-freed-23-08-2007/|website=CBS|accessdate=September 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFebruary 22, 1974: [[Samuel Byck]] planned to kill [[Richard Nixon|Nixon]] by crashing a commercial airliner into the [[White House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.9-11commission.gov/report/911Report_Notes.htm |title=9/11 report notes |publisher=[[9/11 Commission]] |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412190717/http://www.9-11commission.gov/report/911Report_Notes.htm |archivedate=April 12, 2016 }}</ref> He [[Aircraft hijacking|hijacked the plane]] on the ground by force after killing a police officer, and was told that it could not take off with the wheel blocks still in place. After he shot both pilots (one later died), an officer named Charles 'Butch' Troyer shot Byck through the plane's door window. He survived long enough to kill himself by shooting.\n\n===Gerald Ford===\n{{main|Gerald Ford assassination attempt in Sacramento|Gerald Ford assassination attempt in San Francisco}}\nSeptember 5, 1975: On the northern grounds of the [[California State Capitol]], [[Lynette Fromme|Lynette \"Squeaky\" Fromme]], a follower of [[Charles Manson]], drew a [[Colt M1911]] .45 caliber pistol on [[Gerald R. Ford|Ford]] when he reached to shake her hand in a crowd. She had four cartridges in the pistol's [[Magazine (firearm)|magazine]] but none in the firing chamber, and as a result, the gun did not fire. She was quickly restrained by Secret Service agent [[Larry Buendorf]]. Fromme was sentenced to life in prison, but was released from custody on August 14, 2009 (two years and eight months after Ford's death in 2006).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/tdih.do?id=5322&action=tdihArticleCategory |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090502134729/http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history.do?id=5322&action=tdihArticleCategory |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 2, 2009 |title=1975 : Ford assassination attempt thwarted |publisher=[[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]] |accessdate=May 6, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nSeptember 22, 1975: In [[San Francisco, California]], only 17 days after Fromme's attempt, [[Sara Jane Moore]] fired a revolver at Ford from 40 feet (12&nbsp;m) away.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/president-ford-survives-second-assassination-attempt|title=1975: President Ford survives second assassination attempt|publisher=History Channel|accessdate=May 8, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106064815/https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/president-ford-survives-second-assassination-attempt|archive-date=January 6, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> A bystander, [[Oliver Sipple]], grabbed Moore's arm and the shot missed Ford, striking a building wall and slightly injuring taxi driver John Ludwig.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randomhouse.com/features/americancentury/imperialpres.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990422154905/http://www.randomhouse.com/features/americancentury/imperialpres.html|archivedate=April 22, 1999|title=The Imperial Presidency 1972-1980|accessdate=May 8, 2007}}</ref> Moore was tried and convicted in federal court, and sentenced to prison for life. She was paroled from a federal prison on December 31, 2007 after serving more than 30 years, one year and five days after Ford's natural death.\n\n===Jimmy Carter===\n[[Raymond Lee Harvey]] was an Ohio-born unemployed American [[Drifter (person)|drifter]]. He was arrested by the [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] after being found carrying a [[starter pistol]] with [[Blank (cartridge)|blank]] rounds, ten minutes before [[Jimmy Carter|Carter]] was to give a speech at the [[Civic Center, Los Angeles, California|Civic Center Mall]] in [[Los Angeles]] on May 5, 1979. Harvey had a history of [[mental illness]],<ref name=\"Time\">[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,920351,00.html \"Skid Row Plot: A scheme to kill Carter?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823095355/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C920351%2C00.html |date=August 23, 2013 }}, ''Time'' May 21, 1979.</ref> but police had to investigate his claim that he was part of a four-man operation to assassinate the president.<ref>\"The Plot to Kill Carter\", ''Newsweek'' May 21, 1979.</ref> According to Harvey, he fired seven blank rounds from the starter pistol on the hotel roof on the night of May 4 to test how much noise it would make. He claimed to have been with one of the plotters that night, whom he knew as \"Julio\". (This man was later identified as a 21-year-old illegal immigrant from Mexico, who gave the name Osvaldo Espinoza Ortiz.)<ref name=\"Time\" /> At the time of his arrest, Harvey had eight spent rounds in his pocket, as well as 70 unspent blank rounds for the gun.<ref name=\"STH\">\"Alleged Carter death plot: man charged\", ''The Sydney Morning Herald'' May 10, 1979.</ref> Harvey was jailed on a $50,000 bond, given his [[Transient laborer|transient]] status, and Ortiz was alternately reported as being held on a $100,000 bond as a [[material witness]]<ref name=\"Time\" /> or held on a $50,000 bond being charged with burglary from a car.<ref name=\"STH\" /> Charges against the pair were ultimately dismissed for a lack of evidence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=264078 |title=Harvey / \"Carter Assassination Plot\", CBS News broadcast |website=Vanderbilt Television News Archive |accessdate=June 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303225619/http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=264078 |archivedate=March 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n[[John Hinckley Jr.]] came close to shooting Carter during his re-election campaign, but he lost his nerve. He would later attempt to kill President Ronald Reagan in March 1981.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Hinckley Jr.: Hunting Carter and Reagan |url=https://www.historyonthenet.com/john-hinckley-jr/ |website=History on the Net |accessdate=August 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Taubman |first1=Philip |title=Investigators Think Hinckley Stalked Carter |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/04/12/us/investigators-think-hinckley-stalked-carter.html |accessdate=August 26, 2018 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Ronald Reagan===\n{{main|Attempted assassination of Ronald Reagan}}\n[[File: President Ronald Reagan moments before he was shot in an assassination attempt 1981.jpg|thumb|[[Ronald Reagan]] waves just before he is shot outside a Washington hotel on March 30, 1981. From left are [[Jerry Parr]], in white trench coat, who pushed Reagan into the limousine; [[press secretary]] [[James Brady]], who was seriously wounded by a gunshot wound to the head; Reagan; aide [[Michael Deaver]]; an unidentified policeman; policeman [[Thomas Delahanty|Thomas K. Delahanty]], who was shot in the neck; and secret service agent [[Timothy J. McCarthy|Tim McCarthy]], who was shot in the stomach.]]\nMarch 30, 1981: As [[Ronald Reagan]] returned to his [[Presidential state car (United States)|limousine]] after speaking at the [[Washington Hilton]] hotel, he and three others were struck by gunfire from would-be assassin [[John Hinckley Jr.]] Reagan was seriously wounded by a bullet that ricocheted off the side of the presidential limousine and hit him in the left underarm, breaking a rib, puncturing a lung, and causing serious internal bleeding. Although \"close to death\" upon arrival at [[George Washington University Hospital]], Reagan was stabilized in the emergency room, then underwent emergency exploratory surgery.<ref name=\"cnn transcript\">{{cite news|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0103/30/lkl.00.html|title=Remembering the Assassination Attempt on Ronald Reagan|date=March 30, 2001|accessdate=December 19, 2007|publisher=CNN}}</ref> He recovered and was released from the hospital on April 11.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/comment/dsouza200406080824.asp|work=National Review|accessdate=February 16, 2009|date=June 8, 2004|title=Purpose|author=[[Dinesh D'Souza|D'Souza, Dinesh]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203070233/http://nationalreview.com/comment/dsouza200406080824.asp <!-- Added by H3llBot -->|archivedate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> Besides Reagan, [[White House Press Secretary|White House press secretary]] [[James Brady]], Secret Service agent [[Tim McCarthy]], and police officer [[Thomas Delahanty]] were also wounded. All three survived, but Brady suffered brain damage and was permanently disabled; Brady's death in 2014 was considered homicide because it was ultimately caused by this injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/james-bradys-death-ruled-homicide-by-dc-medical-examiner/2014/08/08/686de224-1f41-11e4-82f9-2cd6fa8da5c4_story.html |title=Medical examiner rules James Brady's death a homicide |website=Washington Post |accessdate=June 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328024710/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/james-bradys-death-ruled-homicide-by-dc-medical-examiner/2014/08/08/686de224-1f41-11e4-82f9-2cd6fa8da5c4_story.html |archivedate=March 28, 2016 }}</ref> \n\nHinckley was immediately arrested, and later said he had wanted to kill Reagan to impress actress [[Jodie Foster]]. He was deemed mentally ill and confined to an institution. Hinckley was released from institutional psychiatric care on September 10, 2016.<ref name=\"foxnews.com\">{{cite news|title=John Hinckley Jr. to begin living full-time in Virginia Sept. 10|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/john-hinckley-jr-leaves-dc-mental-hospital-for-virginia|accessdate=December 6, 2018|agency=[[Fox News]]|date=September 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===George H. W. Bush===\nApril 13, 1993: According to Kuwaiti authorities, fourteen Kuwaiti and Iraqi men believed to be working for [[Saddam Hussein]] smuggled bombs into [[Kuwait]], planning to assassinate former president [[George H. W. Bush|Bush]] by a car bomb during his visit to [[Kuwait University]] three months after he had left office (in January 1993).<ref>{{Cite news|title=U.S. Strikes Iraq for Plot to Kill Bush|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/inatl/longterm/iraq/timeline/062793.htm|date=Jun 27, 1993|first=David|last=Von Drehle|work=[[The Washington Post]]|first2=R. Jeffrey|last2=Smith|lastauthoramp=yes|accessdate=February 14, 2011}}</ref> Kuwaiti officials claimed to have foiled the alleged plot and arrested the suspected assassins. Two of the suspects, Wali Abdelhadi Ghazali and Raad Abdel-Amir al-Assadi, retracted their confessions at the trial, claiming that they were coerced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fas.org/irp/agency/doj/oig/fbilab1/05bush2.htm |title=The Bush assassination attempt |publisher=[[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]]/[[FBI Laboratory]] report |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070402200736/http://www.fas.org/irp/agency/doj/oig/fbilab1/05bush2.htm |archivedate=April 2, 2007 }}</ref> Then-president [[Bill Clinton]] responded by launching a [[1993 cruise missile strikes on Iraq|cruise missile attack on an Iraqi intelligence building]] in [[Baghdad]].  The plot was used as one of the justifications for the [[Iraq Resolution]].\n\nAn analysis by the CIA's Counter-Terrorism Center concludes the assassination plot was likely fabricated by Kuwaiti authorities.<ref>{{cite news|title=CIA SAYS IRAQI PLOT TO KILL BUSH MAY BE FICTION|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1993-05-27-9305270298-story.html|date=May 27, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\n===Bill Clinton===\n*January 21, 1994: Ronald Gene Barbour, a retired military officer and freelance writer, plotted to kill Clinton while the president was jogging. Barbour returned to Florida a week later without having fired the shots at the president, who was on a state visit to [[Russia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/02/19/us/unemployed-man-is-charged-with-threat-to-kill-president.html |title=Unemployed Man Is Charged With Threat to Kill President |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 19, 1994 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517033656/http://www.nytimes.com/1994/02/19/us/unemployed-man-is-charged-with-threat-to-kill-president.html |archivedate=May 17, 2017 }}</ref> Barbour was sentenced to five years in prison and was released in 1998.\n*September 12, 1994: [[Frank Eugene Corder]] flew a stolen single-engine [[Cessna]] onto the White House lawn and crashed into a tree. Corder, a truck driver from Maryland who reportedly had alcohol problems, allegedly tried to hit the White House. He was killed in the crash. The president and first family were not home at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9903E1D6173BF930A2575AC0A962958260 |title=Crash at the White House: The Overview |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 14, 1994 |accessdate=August 27, 2008 |first=Maureen |last=Dowd |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124161827/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9903E1D6173BF930A2575AC0A962958260 |archivedate=January 24, 2009 }}</ref>\n*October 29, 1994: [[Francisco Martin Duran]] fired at least 29 shots with a semiautomatic rifle at the White House from a fence overlooking the north lawn, thinking that [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]] was among the men in dark suits standing there (Clinton was inside). Three tourists, Harry Rakosky, Ken Davis and Robert Haines, tackled Duran before he could injure anyone. Found to have a [[suicide]] note in his pocket, Duran was sentenced to 40 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prop1.org/park/pave/rev6.htm |title=Summary Statement of Facts (The September 12, 1994 Plane Crash and The October 29, 1994 Shooting) Background Information on the White House Security Review |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927212928/http://prop1.org/park/pave/rev6.htm |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n*1996: During his visit to the [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation]] (APEC) forum in Manila, Clinton's motorcade was rerouted before it was to drive over a bridge. Service officers had intercepted a message suggesting that an attack was imminent, and [[Lewis Merletti]], the director of the Secret Service, ordered the motorcade to be re-routed. An intelligence team later discovered a bomb under the bridge. Subsequent U.S. investigation \"revealed that [the plot] was masterminded by a Saudi terrorist living in Afghanistan named [[Osama bin Laden]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/philippines/6867331/Osama-bin-Laden-came-within-minutes-of-killing-Bill-Clinton.html |title=Osama bin Laden came within minutes of killing Bill Clinton |last=Leonard |first=Tom |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=December 22, 2009 |accessdate=June 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091225150252/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/philippines/6867331/Osama-bin-Laden-came-within-minutes-of-killing-Bill-Clinton.html |archivedate=December 25, 2009 }}</ref>\n*October 2018: A package containing a [[pipe bomb]] addressed to wife [[Hillary Clinton]] and sent to their home in [[Chappaqua, New York]] was intercepted by Secret Service. It was [[October 2018 United States mail bombing attempts|one of several mailed to other Democratic leaders in the same week]], including former president [[Barack Obama]].<ref name=cnn>[https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/24/politics/bill-clinton-hillary-clinton-chappaqua/index.html 'Act of terror': Bombs sent to CNN, Clintons, Obamas, Holder] CNN, October 24, 2018</ref> [[Bill Clinton]] was at the Chappaqua home when the package was intercepted, while Hillary was in Florida campaigning for Democrats.<ref>https://www.indystar.com/story/news/2018/10/24/bomb-found-home-hillary-and-bill-clinton-new-york-city-suburb/1748676002/</ref> Fingerprint DNA revealed that the package was sent by Florida resident Cesar Sayoc, who was captured two days after the package was intercepted.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/26/politics/suspicious-packages-arrest/index.html|title=Bomb suspect arrest: What we know about Cesar Sayoc|author1=Jason Hanna |author2=Evan Perez |author3=Scott Glover|work=CNN|access-date=October 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026165125/https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/26/politics/suspicious-packages-arrest/index.html|archive-date=October 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Prosecutors sought a life sentence for Sayoc, but due to the bombs being intentionally made not to go off the judge instead sentenced him to 20 years in prison.\n\n===George W. Bush===\n{{main|Assassination attempts against George W. Bush}}\nFebruary 7, 2001: While President [[George W. Bush]] was in the White House, Robert Pickett, standing outside the perimeter fence, discharged a number of shots from a weapon in the direction of the White House. He was sentenced to three years in prison.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timelines.latimes.com/us-presidential-assassinations-and-attempts/ |title=U.S. presidential assassinations and attempts |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20131204011625/http://timelines.latimes.com/us-presidential-assassinations-and-attempts/ |archivedate=December 4, 2013  }}</ref> \n\nMay 10, 2005: While President Bush was giving a speech in the [[Freedom Square, Tbilisi|Freedom Square]] in [[Tbilisi]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Vladimir Arutyunian]] threw a live [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]-made [[RGD-5]] [[hand grenade]] toward the podium. The grenade had its pin pulled, but did not explode because a red tartan handkerchief was wrapped tightly around it, preventing the safety lever from detaching.<ref>[https://www.fbi.gov/page2/jan06/grenadeattack011106.htm US FBI report into the attack and investigation] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070411035739/http://www.fbi.gov/page2/jan06/grenadeattack011106.htm |date=April 11, 2007 }}.</ref> After escaping that day, Arutyunian was arrested in July 2005. During his arrest, he killed an Interior Ministry agent. He was convicted in January 2006 and given a [[life sentence]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/europe/01/11/georgia.grenade/index.html |title=Bush grenade attacker gets life |publisher=CNN |date=January 11, 2006 |accessdate=May 6, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704105908/http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/europe/01/11/georgia.grenade/index.html |archivedate=July 4, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/page2/jan06/grenadeattack011106.htm|title=The case of the failed hand grenade attack|publisher=[[FBI]] Press Room|date=January 11, 2006|accessdate=May 6, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070411035739/http://www.fbi.gov/page2/jan06/grenadeattack011106.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate =April 11, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Barack Obama===\n{{main|Assassination threats against Barack Obama}}\n*April 2009: A plot to assassinate Obama at the [[Alliance of Civilizations]] summit in [[Istanbul]], Turkey was discovered after a man of Syrian origins carrying forged [[Al-Jazeera]] TV [[press credentials]] was found. The man confessed to the Turkish security services details of his plan to kill Obama with a knife with three alleged accomplices.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.edition.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/04/06/turkey.assassination.plot/index.html |title=Plot to assassinate Obama foiled in Turkey |work=CNN |author=Ed Henry |date=April 6, 2009 |accessdate=June 21, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703004736/http://www.edition.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/04/06/turkey.assassination.plot/index.html |archivedate=July 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n*November 2011: [[2011 White House shooting|Oscar Ramiro Ortega-Hernandez]] hit the White House with several rounds fired from a semi-automatic rifle. No one was injured. However, a window was broken.<ref name=Leonnig>{{cite news|title=Secret Service fumbled response after gunman hit White House residence in 2011 |last=Leonnig |first=Carol D. |date=September 27, 2014 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/secret-service-stumbled-after-gunman-hit-white-house-residence-in-2011/2014/09/27/d176b6ac-442a-11e4-b437-1a7368204804_story.html |accessdate=December 14, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108004003/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/secret-service-stumbled-after-gunman-hit-white-house-residence-in-2011/2014/09/27/d176b6ac-442a-11e4-b437-1a7368204804_story.html |archivedate=November 8, 2016 }}</ref> He was sentenced to 25 years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oscar Ramiro Ortega-Hernandez, man who shot at White House, gets 25 years |author=<!--Staff--> |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 31, 2014 |publisher=[[Fox News Channel]] |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/03/31/oscar-ramiro-ortega-hernandez-man-who-shot-at-white-house-gets-25-years/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150111232958/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/03/31/oscar-ramiro-ortega-hernandez-man-who-shot-at-white-house-gets-25-years/ |archivedate=January 11, 2015 |accessdate=March 10, 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n*April 2013: [[April 2013 ricin letters|Another attempt]] was made when a letter laced with [[ricin]], a deadly poison, was sent to President Obama.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/18/politics/tainted-letter-intercepted/index.html |title=FBI confirms letters to Obama, others contained ricin |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=October 14, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130825152537/http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/18/politics/tainted-letter-intercepted/index.html |archivedate=August 25, 2013 }}</ref>\n*October 2018: [[October 2018 United States mail bombing attempts|A package]] that contained a fabricated pipe bomb was sent to former president Obama at his home in Washington, D.C. The package was intercepted by [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Merrit |title=Apparent 'Pipe Bombs' Mailed To Clinton, Obama And CNN |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/10/24/660161491/u-s-intercepts-suspicious-packages-addressed-to-clinton-and-obama |accessdate=October 25, 2018 |work=NPR |date=October 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\"Potentially destructive devices\" sent to Clinton, Obama, CNN prompt massive response |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/live-news/suspicious-packages-pipe-bomb-clinton-obama-cnn-nyc-wasserman-schultz-office-live-updates/ |accessdate=October 25, 2018 |work=CBS News |date=October 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Donald Trump===\n{{main|Attempted assassination of Donald Trump}}\n*June 2016: [[Michael Steven Sandford]], a British national with a history of mental illness, tried to seize a police officer's pistol at a Trump rally in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], in an attempt to assassinate Trump (then the presumptive Republican nominee). Sandford had reportedly been planning such an action for over a year. The pistol caught in the holster and Sandford was immediately arrested, and eventually deported to the [[United Kingdom]]. The incident received less coverage in the United States than in Britain, where it led to a debate over the [[Mental Capacity Act 2005]] and was the subject of a BBC documentary.<ref name=\"Frizzell29January2017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/jan/27/brit-who-tried-kill-trump-michael-sandford-donald-bbc-president|title='He never even watched the news' \u2013 the Brit who tried to kill Trump|last=Frizzell|first=Nell|date=January 27, 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=January 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n*November 2017: A man affiliated with the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] was arrested by the [[Philippine National Police]] in [[Rizal Park]] for reportedly planning to assassinate President Trump during the [[ASEAN Summit]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/how-the-secret-service-foiled-an-assassination-attempt-against-trump-by-isis? |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |title=How the Secret Service Foiled an Assassination Plot Against Trump by ISIS |first=Marlow |last=Stern |date=October 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n*October 2018: William Clyde Allen III, a U.S. Navy veteran, sent a letter containing crushed [[Ricinus|castor beans]] to President Trump. The letter did not reach the White House as it was seized by the Secret Service. He sent similar letters to Secretary of Defense [[James Mattis]] and Chief of Naval Operations Adm. [[John M. Richardson (admiral) |John Richardson]]. Allen was arrested on October 3, 2018 in Utah.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barr |first1=Luke |title=Man accused of sending letters laced with ricin 'wanted to send a message' |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/man-accused-sending-letters-laced-ricin-wanted-send/story?id=58309953 |accessdate=October 9, 2018 |publisher=ABC News |date=October 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Whitehurst |first1=Lindsay |title=Authorities Arrest Navy Veteran in Connection With Suspicious Envelopes Sent to President Trump |url=http://time.com/5414790/utah-man-ricin-letter-trump-arrested/ |accessdate=October 9, 2018 |magazine=Time |date=October 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Copp |first1=Tara |title=Navy vet arrested for allegedly trying to poison Mattis and the Navy's top officer |url=https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2018/10/03/navy-vet-william-clyde-allen-iii-arrested-in-ricin-poison-case/ |accessdate=October 9, 2018 |publisher=Military Times |date=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Death rumored to be an assassination==\nIn June 1923, President [[Warren G. Harding]] set out on a cross-country \"Voyage of Understanding\", planning to meet with citizens and explain his policies. During this trip, he became the first president to visit [[Alaska]], which was then a U.S. [[Territory of Alaska|territory]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historytogo.utah.gov/utah_chapters/from_war_to_war/presidenthardings1923visittoutah.html|title=President Harding's 1923 Visit to Utah|last=Reeve|first=W. Paul|date=July 1995|work=History Blazer|access-date=June 14, 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150502040538/http://historytogo.utah.gov/utah_chapters/from_war_to_war/presidenthardings1923visittoutah.html|archive-date=May 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRumors of [[political corruption|corruption]] in the Harding administration were beginning to circulate in [[Washington, D.C.]], by 1923, and Harding was profoundly shocked by a long message he received while in Alaska, apparently detailing illegal activities by his own cabinet that were allegedly unknown to him. At the end of July, while traveling south from Alaska through [[British Columbia]], he developed what was thought to be a severe case of [[food poisoning]]. He gave the final speech of his life to a large crowd at the University of Washington Stadium (now [[Husky Stadium]]) at the [[University of Washington]] campus in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. A scheduled speech in [[Portland, Oregon]], was canceled. The president's train proceeded south to [[San Francisco]]. Upon arriving at the [[Palace Hotel, San Francisco|Palace Hotel]], he developed [[pneumonia]]. Harding died in his hotel room of either a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] or a [[stroke]] at 7:35&nbsp;p.m. (19:35) on August 2, 1923. The formal announcement, printed in ''[[The New York Times]]'' of that day, stated: \"A [[stroke]] of [[apoplexy]] was the cause of death.\" He had been ill exactly one week.<ref>{{cite news|title=Harding a Farm Boy Who Rose by Work |url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/1102.html |quote=Nominated for the Presidency as a compromise candidate and elected by a tremendous majority because of a reaction against the policies of his predecessor, Warren Gamaliel Harding, twenty-ninth President of the United States, owed his political elevation largely to his engaging personal traits, his ability to work in harmony with the leaders of his party, and the fact that he typified in himself the average prosperous American citizen. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=July 21, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015045948/http://nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/1102.html |archivedate=October 15, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n[[United States Navy|Naval]] physicians surmised that Harding had suffered a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]]. The Hardings' personal medical advisor, homeopath and [[Surgeon General of the United States|Surgeon General]] [[Charles E. Sawyer]], disagreed with the diagnosis. His wife, [[Florence Harding]], refused permission for an [[autopsy]], which soon led to speculation that the president had been the victim of a plot, possibly carried out by his wife, as Harding apparently had been unfaithful to the first lady. [[Gaston Means|Gaston B. Means]], an amateur historian and [[Gadfly (social)|gadfly]], noted in his book ''The Strange Death of President Harding'' (1930) that the circumstances surrounding his death led to suspicions that he had been poisoned. A number of individuals attached to him, both personally and politically, would have welcomed Harding's death, as they would have been disgraced in association by Means' assertion of Harding's \"imminent impeachment\".\n\n==See also==\n*[[Assassination of Robert F. Kennedy]], Democratic presidential candidate, on June 5, 1968\n*[[George Wallace#Democratic presidential primaries of 1972 and assassination attempt|Attempted assassination of George Wallace]], Democratic presidential candidate, on May 15, 1972\n*[[Thomas R. Marshall#Assassination attempt|Attempted assassination of Thomas R. Marshall]], vice president, on July 2, 1915\n*[[Curse of Tippecanoe]]\n*[[Kennedy curse]]\n*[[List of assassinated and executed heads of state and government]]\n*[[List of incidents of political violence in Washington, D.C.]]\n*[[List of White House security breaches]]\n*[[Threatening the President of the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |ref=Hammond |last=Hammond |first=John Hays |authorlink=John Hays Hammond |year=1935 |title=The Autobiography of John Hays Hammond |url=https://archive.org/details/autobiographyofj0001hamm |url-access=registration |location=New York |publisher=Farrar & Rinehart |isbn=978-0-405-05913-1 |oclc=867910}} Free at the Internet Archive: [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.60381/page/n9 Volume 1] and [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.179915/page/n7 Volume 2].\n* {{cite magazine |ref=Hampton |last=Hampton |first=Benjamin B. |date=April 1, 1910 |title=The Vast Riches of Alaska: Will the Morgan-Guggenheim Combination Acquire Them, or Will They Benefit the Whole People? |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R4BIAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA450-IA2#v=twopage&q&f=false |magazine=Hampton's Magazine |volume=24 |issue=1 |pages=451\u2013468}}\n* {{cite book |ref=Harris |last1=Harris |first1=Charles H., III |last2=Sadler |first2=Louis R. |year=2009 |title=The Secret War in El Paso: Mexican Revolutionary Intrigue, 1906\u20131920 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4UYzDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=twopage&q&f=false |loc